deck_excerpt: Swordsoul (Xianjing) archetype. You have access to a few key specific floodgates, as well as powerful tools that help break boards and set up interrup
deck_description: Sword Soul deck. The draw of the deck is the powerful Synchros it can make, in particularly Cheng Ying's ability to be 2ish interruptions provided you can proc him. So why Tenyis? A few reasons. Firstly, I'm partial to more tribal decks, and having a general Wyrm engine appeals to me. Secondly, I suspect it increases consistency, and it certainly increases explosiveness, playing more like the combo decks I am used to. Lastly, running this package enablers me to play more floodgates in the Extra Deck. Lastly, being far less Normal Summon reliant means the deck plays Sphere Mode quite well. This version of the deck is very good at cracking boards, even just using engine cards and the maindeck staples. The side deck particularly emphasizes this - we'd prefer to go first, but if you make us go second you might actually have a worse time in some circumstances. Let's go over the list.  Long Yuan is one of the most important Sword Souls monsters, since it by itself makes Baroness De Fleur or more importantly Cheng Ying. It also doesn't conflict with Sphere Mode. Mo Ye is powerful, getting to draw a card is great and our main extender out of the Extra Deck is a Synchro 8 that counts as an interruption, very beautiful. I think you have to run 3 of both of these. Tai A is less important, but you want to play 2 so that you're less likely to banish it with Desires, since it is a common search off of the Rota, and leads to Synchro 8 Spam. While these are normal summons, neither have to be normal summoned, and you will start your plays sometimes by resurrecting them with the Monster Reborn of the archetype, or the Shaman of the Tenyi, and yes, this is actually a lot more realistic than you might think. We play a lot of Tenyi monsters and any 2 of them into Shaman is totally believable, and in fact you'll often get some other value off of Tenyi plays in the process. The Rota is obligatory, it's the Rota, the field spell is this one card you can search to spam out 8s and is just good enough as an engine card to run 1 of it IMO. I'd consider cutting it, but the Synchro 8 Spam is a neat option that merits use in some matchups anyways, because of Dragite, and because of having a larger full combo.  For Tenyi monsters, we run 2 of the most important Tenyi monsters, Vishuda. You could honestly bump this up to 3 and be happy, it is the most valuable of the Tenyi cards. Like Alpha, this can bounce a monster, including bouncing a Kaiju back into your own hand. You can break some pretty mighty boards with this deck, because including this card you're running as many as 13 board breaking cards vs hefy boards, meaning when you know (or smell) that you're going second you come in with a great chance to actually bust some boards before making Wyrm plays. It's also an engine card. Adhara gives you access to Level 9 Synchro plays and refills your hand for Long Yuan, helping you say search it or the trap, for making those Level 9s is particularly noteworthy. Ashuna + any other Tenyi is full combo. Okay, not quite, but it's a good enough starter to combos that you want to see Ashuna. And Vessel just increases your chances of seeing the right Tenyi's, the card is either dead or a must negate generally speaking. I think it's worth it to run, because you have so many Tenyi cards, and this makes your big Tenyi combo plays way more common.  1 Gold Sarc. Hate the card, but we're on 3 Adhara, and it has other utility. In fact this and Called By The Grave are both run in this list primarily to proc Cheng Ying, hilariously enough, but obviously Called might make the cut anyways.  3 Pot of Desires. Banishes barely matter to this deck, you'll sometimes gimp yourself but more often than not it is free consistency, and you can afford to run the numbers to almost never feel this. I still struggle a little bit to understand why Pot feels better here than in some other homes, but it does, though that perception could simply be my own luck changing. The more I test the more I see, in this archetype you want the cards more than to see 1 specific engine card, so Prosperity is probably worse.  Forbidden Droplet is live often enough going first, and necessary often enough going second, and actually makes the cut on the merit of making us lose going second significantly less. Tenyi monsters actually like being in the GY sometimes, so even if you pitch 3 cards a lot of the time you'll still have solid plays to make after that to break boards. Tactics, in turn, is better going first, being either a consistency card or a way to make hand traps worse. It makes the main deck because going second against Dragoon, it is just GG for the Dragoon player, and Dragoon will be important to handle until it is banned. Solemn Strike is an amazing going first card that stays in whenever we are going first. However, like the rest of this package is is good going second as well, an actual hard negate at Spell Speed 3 that also negates summons is very good.  So, for the extra deck. 2 Chi Xiao, because this is like the archetype's Needlefibre, and it is also on of your main bosses and your main way to trigger Cheng Ying at the right time. You need 2 for your grind game. 1 Cheng Ying, you must also run this, this card is the reason to play the deck. A little bit tricky to activate its effect and time it for the right disruption, but very powerful on the face of it. 1 Draco Bersker. You're often locked into Wyrm monsters because of Ashuna, and this gives you the very important second rank 8 to make in those situations, and as a bonus it it good going first or second and trigger's Cheng Ying. 1 Yazi. You can make this with level manipulation, but you also make this with Long Yuan and a Adhara. It pops a card before summoning out Tai A and is fuel for Tai A, and is good going second, but I rarely actually make it. You need a level 7 for some boards (to not waste resources) and this is the only Wyrm, but it is pretty good in the deck. 2 Baxia - shuffling cards into the deck is good going second, even if it does target. You make this into Chaofeng in some of your combos. giving you an amazing Floodgate against Light attribute based decks. With the help of level modulation, you can occasionally make Yazi into Chaofeng locking decks out of Dark monsters, similarly if not more broken. Dragite is a generic backrow negate, but you turn him on with Mo Ye naturally and it contributes to the ability to actually put up real negates. Baroness De Fleur is a way to break boards that is also one omni-negate and a monster Reborn. I don't know if this will be legal at the same time as Sword Soul, at least right away, but for now I'm being an optimist and hoping we get it. I'm on 1 Shenshen. Not only is this a reasonably floodgate against a lot of decks, but you make it easily throughout your combos, and you make it off of Chi Xiao and then revive it in some Tenyi combos, so it isn't going without support. It seems good to have as an option. Lastly we run 1 Omega, because we need generic and powerful Synchro 8s and yeah, Omega still makes the cut. I find myself never making this, but it is strictly better than any of the alternatives. Lastly we have some Tenyi monsters, these make the Tenyi engine go Brr, and Shaman makes Sphere Mode kind of a breeze.  So the side deck. The deck seems powerful enough at putting up interruptions and pressure going first that I wanted to lean on a side deck built around breaking boards. The idea is that if we can pretty consistently break even the beefiest of boards we can decide to go second, maybe shake up somebody's siding plan, but also I don't think the deck needs a lot more going first. You're usually siding out some number of the pots, as well as TTT (which stays in over Sphere Mode in matchups that swing down to Dragoon). So here are the numbers. 3 Sphere Mode. Yes this eats up your normal summons, but this isn't as relevant as you might think. It also immediately solves a lot of problem boards, and again helps enable us to eat even really beefy boards. Because it can't be targeted you can't return this to your hand with Vishuda, but you can with Alpha, meaning this + Alpha if they have a 6 monster board, but in practice if they do they have an interruption to prevent this anyways, so it isn't as relevant as it is with the Kaijus. Speaking of 2 Gadarla, 2 Alpha. Gadarla tributes over Wind Barrier Statue and is level 8, and you can bounce it with Alpha or Vishuda to get an extra tribute. Did I mention this deck was good at breaking boards? Alpha is Alpha, it is the new Pankratops, and is just as broken. 1 Pankratops because even though it doesn't play into the loops, it doubles as spell and trap removal, making it still slightly more valuable than Alpha despite lacking the synergy. Also the more different names we run the more of these effects, again you're bringing in whichever 13 board breakers are most relevant including many different names and effects that synergize. You also aren't obligated to bring them in. If Sphere Mode is bad, leave in Tactics, it is as simple as that. I wanted some ways to handle backrow beside Pankratops, so I went with Twintwister. I just noticed that a lot of the decks you would bring it in against getting the banish isn't as relevant as getting that second set card. Then Red Reboot, because it is Red Reboot. Goodbye trap deck. For my last option I had space to play going first cards, and I tested a lot of Solemn Judgement. But in thinking about the meta, both now and in the future, I'm expecting the top decks in the current meta will stay powerful, and that this deck and Flundereeze become contenders, and I'm seeing a lot of overlap in the decks that are weak to this card. Against Flundereeze it stops tributing, against Drytron it stops ritual summoning, against Rokkets it stops seal, it stops Romulus, it stops Darkness Metal, it basically neuters a lot of plays. Sure in the mirror and against Prank Kids it does nothing, but in Tribrigade it shuts down their whole mechanic, against any Isolde abuse no Isolde. So you've got like Phantom Knights, the Mirror, Prank Kids, and Sky Striker, and a myriad of decks this doesn't hit that hard, but it does hit a whole swath of them a lot harder than it hits you, especially going first. Now game 3 they have to side in that backrow removal and you might've already pulled em out if you're going second. It basically lets me hit a swath of decks, including some of the threats I expect to still be relevant and some newcomers, so for theorycrafting it seems like a good place to start, since it just hits all the best decks but the mirror, with a couple notable exceptions, and there wasn't space to have 3 specific hand traps to bring in for every random combo matchup. Against a lot of those decks Sphere Mode is fine, Desires is fine, or Tactics is fine, and will generally be higher impact than any hand trap.

deck_excerpt: A fun and competitive way to play Drytrons that doesn't make your opponent want to quit the game while bringing back Nekroz.
deck_description:
This deck was inspired by the efficiency of the Drytron engine for ritual monsters. Look I love the color blue, blue cards are awesome, and not these knock off dollar store blue cards called "link" monster... even if they do dominate the meta. This deck runs 3 engines:
  1. Drytrons: Purely to search out ritual monsters, spells, and summon Mu Beta Fafnir to help with ritual summoning with Meteonis Drytron.
  2. Nekroz: These are the blue cards we're looking for. Nekroz monsters are power crept in the game, although their search power and consistency is still unmatched my most deck and should not be overlooked. Unicore is a skill drain for all extra deck monsters. You see that Dragoon? What's that it can't be targeted or destroyed by battle? With my homie Nekroz of Unicore Dragoon is just a 3k beat stick that my blue bois can steam roll over.
  3. Fairies: Look, Herald of Ultimatness is amazing, but popping off with Drytrons and having him on the field with 4 fairies in your hand as omni negates isn't fun for me. I like to play with my opponent, not stop them from doing anything fun. If you want meta go play any of the meta Drytron Fairy deck and make people hate you at locals. Now for what we play. Benten needs to be banned but until it is run him, Diviner, Orange Light, and Eva. I would run 3 Diviners but I'm making this profile for someone who doesn't have 3. All of these are good cards and with diviner being able to become a level 6 when sending arc light with her effect and is a tuner means you can actually synchro level 8 monsters. More on that later.
This deck has one main goal:
  1. Get Unicore on the field alongside your strong ritual monsters (Draconids, Valkyrus, Areadbhair). Non of your monsters are extra deck monsters meaning Unicore only effects your oppenent. All of your strong monsters can still use their effects because their rituals.
How do we achieve this goal?:
  1. Drytron comes in handi for this. In my mind they are the fuel for the entire decks engine. The most important ones, in this order, are Alpha, Zeta, Gamma, Delta. As long as all 4 exist in your hand/field/GY you can cycle through them all each turn. If you have all 4 available, go through them in this order:
    1. Start with Alpha: Get any ritual monster you may need
    2. Zeta: Get a ritual spell. Meteonis can summon all ritual monsters including the harder to summon Nekroz ones (Areadbhair/Valkrus/Trishula) as long as their in the GY (so dump them to the GY for a Drytron effect). I always want a Meteonis before the Nekroz specific rituals. Nekroz Kaleidoscope is the next best, followed by Cycle, then Mirror.
    3. Delta: Reveal that ritual monster or spell that you will always have in your hand and get a free draw card.
    4. Gamma: Instant Mu Beta Fafnir summon, materials can be used to ritual summon, dump Draconids from deck, use meteonis drytron to ritual Draconids from grave, lower Mu beta fafnir attack to bring back Meteonis to hand, profit.
  2. The Nekroz monsters are really good at searching themselves but for the most part I just use them as tribute fodder for the Drytrons then bring them back from grave, use their in hand effects, or straight up summon them.
The extra deck contains some creatures they are not meant to be summoned but instead meant to be sent off of Kaleidoscope. What this means is you can trade these out for any other extra deck Synchro of Fusion with the same levels and they will serve the same purpose, although I picked these for a specific reason and will note them below. These include:
  1. Herald of Arc Light (also sent to grave with Diviner of Herald). I would keep this becuase its synergy with Faries is too good.
  2. Elder Entity N'tss (I've personally made a Meta Dragoon player at locals scoop because I destroyed their $100 dragoon with this with the Unicore play I describe below. I will always run this. That's what you get for playing a meta deck against actual 12 year olds trying to have fun at locals you ass. As an adult I feel responsible to right these poor kids when someone is trying way too hard to win. We need new people to be in this game to keep it alive and it's our responsibility to make sure they have a good experience and teach them nicely. Laughing at them when you beat them with a $1,000 deck against their structure deck their parents bought them is not cool. Ok, rant over).
  3. Stardust Dragon is a good level 8 to send or summon with Herald. I would keep this as a level 8.
  4. Trishula is just a level 9 to send for a Brionac and Clausolas summon, replaceable with another level 10.
  5. Ruddy Rose is a level 10 for a Brinac and Unicore summon, replaceable with any other level 10. I just think the secret rare of this looks beautiful and I happened to pull one.
  6. 2 Stardust Divine Sifr. 2 level 12's is very smart because with Kaleidoscope you can summon:
    1.  2 Brionacs (6+6)
    2. Valkyrus and Unicore (8+4)
    3. Trishula and Clausolas (9+3)
    4. Not to mention when this card is in the grave due to Kaleidoscope you can resummon a properly Synchroed Stardust Dragon from the Grave. This card does a lot of work in this deck
It's hard to lay out any one specific combo because this deck has so many ways to get to the same end board. I mean half your cards say something along the lines of "search desired card". This deck is more about what you're trying to do and less about how you get there, because you almost always get there. Just don't get Droll and Lock Bird'ed. Some fun things this deck can do in situations:
  1. From hand Nekroz of Valkyrus can end the battle phase instantly. Many times when you have Unicore on the field people try to attack over him so their monsters have their effects back; this tells them no.
  2. If you're able to get 2 Brionac in your hand, play Nekroz Kaleidoscope to send a level 12, special summon both the Brionacs, then XYZ into Gauntles Launcher for the memes of destroying stuff on the field.
  3. If your oppenent summons the dreaded Dragoon and doesn't negate the Kaleidoscope while you attempt to summon Unicore you're in for some fun.  Play Kaleidoscope to send Elder Entity N'tss to summon Unicore. Unicore on summon shuts off all extra deck monster effect, meaning Dragoon is just a sad dragonborn sorcerer with no spell slots left (D&D reference for those who don't understant). That Elder Entity N'tss that you sent to the graveyard can now target the Dragoon and destroy it. LOL.
  4. If you send Arc Light off Diviner of the Herald to make him a level 6 you can synchro with a level 2 to actually summon stardust dragon which is fun. Then if you Kaleidoscope the Stardust Sifr you can banish Sifr  to resummon stardust dragon since you were able to properly synchro startdust. Pretty cool imo. This is only possible with Diviner of the Herald.
Good luck, duelist.

deck_excerpt: This is a Despia Darklord deck that can make up to 5 or more interactions. Below is a link showing of an example combo.  https://www.duelingbook.com
deck_description: This deck specializes in making a very strong first turn board using just two cards with up to 5 or more interactions. I will both explain the combo and post a replay showing a general first turn combo in the deck summary. Step 1: All you need to do the combo is Ready Fusion and any normal summonable monster. Step 2: You must special summon Allvain the Essence of Vanity and normal summon a monster. Step 2: Link summon Crystron Halqifibrax and activate its effect. Step 3: Summon Deskbot 001 from deck using Halqifibrax effect. Step 4: Make Mecha Phantom Beast Auroradon +3 tokens and Summon Deskbot 001 using it's effect. Step 4: Synchro summon Shooting Riser Dragon using 2 tokens and Deskbot 001. With Shooting riser's effect you must send a level 2 monster to the grave for the next step of the combo. (Ex: PSY-framegear Gamma). Step 5: Synchro Summon Chaos Ruler, the Chaotic Magical Dragon and PROFIT. The combo can continue in many paths from here but for the sake of efficiency I will end it here. Siding: You may side Evenly Matched into backrow heavy decks or decks that make a stong turn one board. Super Polymerization and the other sided fusion monsters may also be good into certain first turn board decks. Branded Opening is good into hand trap decks but locks you out of your bread and butter combo. Notes: If you want to make this deck 100% TCG I would recommend a second copy of Allvain. If it's more readily available in the future, Master Flare Hyperion can be used as an alternative to Baroness De Fleur.

deck_excerpt: My build for a Resonator/Red Dragon Archfiend deck for the October 2021 TCG format. This is how the King duels!
deck_description: This is my current build for Red Dragon Archfiend, Resonators, Red Supernova Dragon turbo, whatever you want to call it. The idea of the deck is to get to our Synchro Monsters as consistently as possible, using Resonators and our Level 4 Monsters to Synchro Summon Red Rising Dragon, then bringing back a Resonator with its effect to use the two Monsters to Synchro Summon once more. The main gameplan is as follows: Special Summon Crimson Resonator with its effect, followed by Normal Summoning a Level 4 Monster, preferably Witch of the Black Forest, or Special Summoning Wandering King Wildwind. Then, Synchro Summon Red Rising Dragon, and use its effect to bring back Crimson Resonator. Use Crimson Resonator's effect to Special Summon two Resonators from our deck whose Levels add up to 4 (preferably Synkron Resonator and Creation Resonator for reasons I'll go into later, but two Red Resonators also works) and use our three Resonators and Red Rising Dragon to Synchro Summon this deck's strongest Monster, Red Supernova Dragon. Red Supernova Dragon combats many Monster-focused strategies by waiting to banish the opponent's field in just the right moment to remove problem cards and stop the opponent's plan in its tracks, and ending games quickly with its extremely high attack power.  The ideal Level 4 Monster to perform this setup with is Witch of the Black Forest. This is because she can search any Monster in our main deck after she's sent to the Graveyard, so using her in a Synchro Summon is excellent. In the above setup, using Crimson Resonator and Witch of the Black Forest to make Red Rising Dragon would allow us to search a Monster, such as Red Familiar. Then, using Synkron Resonator as one of the Tuners for Red Supernova Dragon allows us to add a Resonator from our Graveyard to our hand, such as the Creation Resonator we also used. Because Red Familiar can tribute itself to bring back a DARK Dragon Synchro from the Graveyard, and Banish itself to change that Synchro's Level, then combining it with the Creation Resonator (Special Summoned, assuming we still have Red Supernova Dragon) allows us to access most of our other Synchros, Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss. In short, this means if we have Crimson Resonator and Witch of the Black Forest in our opening hand, we have the setup for not only Red Supernova Dragon, but also for another powerful Synchro Monster the following turn. Alternatively, if we open with Crimson Resonator, Red Familiar, and Wandering King Wildwind, we can achieve something similar by Special Summoning Crimson Resonator and Wandering King Wildwind with their respective effects, Synchro Summoning Red Rising Dragon and Red Supernova Dragon as normal, but then Normal Summoning Red Familiar and Special Summoning Creation Resonator. Tribute Red Familiar for its effect to bring back Red Rising Dragon, then use it and Creation Resonator to make Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss, similar to the above setup with Witch of the Black Forest, but on the same turn we Summon Red Supernova Dragon. Regardless, when Abyss deals battle damage we can bring back Synkron Resonator and make Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Bane. This would normally deprive us of Abyss's amazing negation effect for the following turn, but Synkron Resonator lets us add Creation Resonator back to our hand once more, which we can then Special Summon and tribute for Bane's effect to bring back Abyss. Afterwards the main use of Bane will be using it to make Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity, either through Bane's own effect, or, if we have two level 1 Resonators in the GY already, we can use Red Rising Dragon to bring them back and make King Calamity before the Battle Phase. This is the general gameplan, of the deck, but Beelze of the Diabolic Dragons and Void Ogre Dragon, provided we can empty our hand of cards, provide a solid backup plan for different scenarios.  Unfortunately, there will be times where we don't have Crimson Resonator available, despite having three copies of it and three copies of the two cards we can use to search it (Resonator Call and Resonator Command) in which case we need to improvise. If Red Resonator is available, along with a Level 4 Monster, we can still go into Red Rising Dragon, but you'll have to stop on a Level 8 Synchro, being Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend, or Chaos Ruler, the Chaotic Magical Dragon, as neither Void Ogre Dragon nor Beelze of the Diabolic Dragons can be summoned this way. (Both require a DARK Tuner). Scarlight is good for clearing the field or simply being "Red Dragon Archfiend", while Chaos Ruler can be more helpful going first as it can dig through the deck to help further our plays next turn, or ideally, find a Synkron Resonator we can use to make Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss, the ideal monster to have if Red Supernova Dragon isn't an option. If not, we may be forced to fall back on Samsara, Dragon of Rebirth, or Black Rose Moonlight Dragon, or, the worst case scenario, nothing at all. This is where we get into the deck's weaknesses; if we can't Synchro Summon on our first turn, there isn't really anything we can do. It's tempting to add Link Monsters to circumvent this, but I couldn't find any that were good enough to justify the space they'd take, and even if we decided to run the Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon engine, it would hurt the deck's consistency and we wouldn't even always be able to have two Monsters we could Summon to make Predaplant Verte Anaconda anyway. Another issue is the deck struggles to play through hand traps; Effect Veiler and Infinite Impermanence in particular can stop us in our tracks, leaving us on a Red Rising Dragon we can't do anything with. Fortunately, this is something we can address with Called by the Grave, which we include in the Main Deck to give us a shot at shutting these cards down. The final weakness worth mentioning is the deck doesn't have much for dealing with Spells and Traps, though Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss, Infinite Impermanence, and Red Reign can help circumvent this, as can the Side Deck.  The Side Deck contains two six-card packages: a Kaiju package, and a Crossout Designator package. The idea here is we can decide which one we need, and take out the same six cards from the Main Deck for either one; the three Red Sprinters, the two Resonator Engines, and the one Chain Resonator. This is the most painless way I've been able to think of to fit these packages in without hurting the deck's consistency too much. The Crossout Designator package is designed for combating hand traps, specifically Ash Blossom and Joyous Spring, Effect Veiler, and Ghost Belle and Haunted Mansion. These are the ones that I've found tend to foil our plans the most, but Nibiru, the Primordial Being, is also a significant threat. Depending on the current climate of the game it may be wise to use that to replace one of the other targets. In fact, in some contexts it might be better to simply have this package in the Main Deck by default, but as this is a non-meta deck I've designed it with the assumption it will usually be used against other non-meta decks, which may or may not be using hand traps at all. The Kaiju engine, however, is simple enough to use, as its main purpose is simply monster removal when going second. However, in this deck specifically there's enough possible interactions that I think it's worth going into in more detail. I've always been fond of Kaijus, as unlike most other outs to dangerous cards, Kaiju Monsters can interact with the rest of your deck in fun ways, with their varied Types, Levels, and Attributes. This deck plays Dogoran, the Mad Flame Kaiju, Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju, and Radian, the Multidimensional Kaiju, along with three Interrupted Kaiju Slumber, as a package to clear out problematic Monsters and possibly enable our Synchro Monsters in one swoop. For example, if we use Interrupted Kaiju Slumber to give ourselves Dogoran and our opponent Gameciel, we can Banish a Red Rising Dragon in the Graveyard to Special Summon two Level 1 Resonators from our Graveyard and use those along with Dogoran to Synchro Summon Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend, or if we have Radian we can use a single Level 1 Resonator to make a Level 8 Synchro Monster. Of course, we can also keep our Kaiju on the field as means of preventing our opponent from using their own Kaijus to out our Synchro Monsters, particularly Red Supernova Dragon. As for the three Lightning Storm, they're a good safe option if we expect to go second and don't think either the two six-card packages are necessary, in which case we simply side out Chain Resonator and the Resonator Engines.  This deck is subject to change and improvement. It's currently my main focus as far as Yu-Gi-Oh is concerned. I may edit this list in the future to keep it up to date, or as further playing reveals improvements to be made. Let's kick this duel into overdrive!

deck_excerpt: Ft. the only 2 good cards from Cyber Strike
deck_description: Yeah everyone hates Dragoon, but this is simply the best deck I can make with Cyberdarks right now. I wanted to make a Cybernetic Horizon-less build because that card kills the deck with its Extra Deck lock into Machines (seriously Konami what's the point of stopping Cyberdarks from accessing Verte Anaconda and Buster Whelp?? And you didn't even release a good Link or fusion spell to make up for it. I hate you). It's a simple build really, similar decks already exist, I just swapped handtraps for extenders. It's still not rogue tier but is better than what Konami calls 'Cyber Style', in my opinion.  *This deck has lots of starters and extenders and can actually play through interruptions, except Droll & Lock, Dimensional Shifter and Nibiru. But depending on your hand you should be able to make Dragoon anyway, as opposite to the "Cyber Style" build which just dies.  *Dragoon is sadly not only way better than Cyberdarkness and Dark End, but also easily accessible so there is no point in not using it -- best win condition of the deck. What does Dragoon gain from protecting Cyberdarks? Well for starters, the buster lock completely invalidates Super Polymerization. And the resource recycling game pretty much guarantees Dragoon will always have something to discard. Plus Cyberdarks add lots of destruction removal so it's not like they do nothing  *The second win condition is the Cyberdark themselves equipped with Dragon Buster Destruction Sword. Try to equip it with Cyberdark Invasion rather than with the effect of the Cyberdark itself; this way, the little dragon will stay equipped even if Keel, Edge and Horn get their effects negated. Even without Dragon Buster, the Cyberdark trio can hold their own with Invasion and Inferno support  *Magicians' Souls lets you draw into your extenders to make Link plays and is a prime Link material itself. It can also fix your hand in a pitch. Send the equips to gain easy card advantage over your opponent. Shuffle REF back in the deck with Illusion of Chaos.  *Add Revsystem with Core when your starting hand lacks extenders.  *Ningirsu The Wold Chalice Warrior should be put over Fossil Warrior Skull Knight to out some troublesome cards but eh, I never needed it so far. BLS + Pegasus + Megafleet should be enough.

deck_excerpt: budget non competitive stardust assault mode deck
deck_description: one card combo, very cheap but suffer a lot if doesn't go first or has it's effect negeted

3 Negates off of 1 Needlefibre? This is why Needlefibre needs to be banned. Okay, Auroradon is actually a card you could maybe hit instead, or you could be stupid and ban Deskbot and every other Tuner Needlefibre can summon, but broken stuff keeps popping up with Needlefibre.  So, this is a shell for that combo. So why this combo, and why this shell? Well for starters, the combo is real. Yes, it can lose to handtraps - in fact you're doing literally everything the most common hand traps hit, searching, summoning, summoning from the GY, activating effects from the GY, activating effects on the field, even making tokens - the combo requires you to dodge or play through hand traps. This is exacerbated by playing Dinosaur, since 1 Lancea is a huge swing in the matchup. Crossout helps but isn't perfect. But the reward for taking that risk is real, a couple serious boss monsters and Herald, which is an omni-negate and a floodgate. And Lost World helps a lot by protecting your monsters from targeting.  So why Dinosaur for this combo? As mentioned above there are cons, mainly that you now lose to basically every hand trap if you don't draw Crossout. Well, the reason is partially for consistency, and partially for power, and partially to mitigate the risks of the combo. It does none of these exceptionally well, but it does all of them well enough. Running 3 Rotas and 3 starters means you're more likely to put up the start without running excess bricks or multiple 1 card Needlefibre packages. Running Lost World helps mitigate the inherent weakness to hand traps. You can also just make Dinosaur plays in the event of hand traps, and my basic mentality when it comes to dinosaur is consistent UTCs are pretty good. That means we have nice consistent 1 card starts, and Babycerasaurus or Petiteranodon + Archosaur will also start you into the combo, so we have multiple ways into it with cards we want to see. Also, Jurrac Aeolo isn't really a brick - not only is it not a Garnet, it isn't a Taketemborg either, since seeing it alongside Oviraptor is the exact same result as seeing Oviraptor + Babycerasaurus, one of your common starts (you can Rota for. That means we can keep it down to 1 Garnet and 2 Taketemborg. Just don't draw Coltwing and you'll be fine. It is also powerful, since you can easily fill those 2 remaining monster zones with good high-quality interruptions in UTC and Pankratops.  So, I started by putting in the bricks and the combo. I hadn't even decided on Dinosaur at that point, I was just looking at easy 1 card Needlefibres and trying to find a home. That became Dinosaur because of Oviraptor, Fossil Dig, and Misc. Misc doesn't really help with the combo the way Lost World does, but it is good nonetheless. Jurrac Aeolo was my next card, a necessary card for going into Needlefibre, but again not really a brick so much as a combo piece. 3 Lost World and 1 Terraforming, this is a big part of the reason to play the combo in this deck. I put in 1 Giant Rex, because you can still make some ordinary Dino plays and the deck wouldn't feel right without him. Sometimes, your combo gets interrupted and you've got to have a backup plan. 2 Archosaur and 2 Pill. You do want to see these, there just isn't space to run 3 each. 3 Babycerasaurus because it is strictly better than Petiteranodon in this deck, but I still want 2 Petiteranodon so you'll occasionally see this and get an extra Pankratops off of your UTC. 2 Tyranno, this is typically your 4th interruption throughout your normal combos, and it is your main back-up plan. Good to see, good to search, good to summon off of pill. 3 Prosperity. This does sort of kill a lot of your backup plans, but all of your main cards leave just about 6 spaces of "filler" and I think having that consistency boost is important. It is also Ash bait, which is really its main purpose, since we're vulnerable to a well-timed Ash. 1 Pankratops, this is a good going second card, but it is also the 5th interruption you put up with Petiteranodon or Pill. You need another high-level monster to summon in your combo. I mean, need is going a little far, but it definitely helps. I like filling all of my monster zones. The rest of the deck is Crossout and random 1 ofs that disrupt the combo if timed right.  This deck goes through the usual Auroradon / Cupid Pitch combo to put up Baroness + Savage + Herald, with Auroradon in the extra monster zone. However, if you have a Baby in your hand or start with a Archosaur + Baby, or just have Pill or UTC in your hand, you add a UTC to that board. You can search UTC to make that even more consistent, and will sometimes add a Pankratops to that board, either by using pill when you have UTC or popping Petiteranodon with UTC. You run 1 Barricadeborg Blocker just to clear up zones so that you can use the Archosaur, Linkuriboh into Secure Gardna for more easy UTCs, and Dollka and Laggia as mascots. For my final cards, I went with I:P into Goddess for a going first option, and Lyna into Accesscode for a going second option, but these slots could be anything and are basically banish fodder (you decide whether you need Dolka/Laggia or Linkuriboh/Gardna).  Getting real LinkFibre era vibes from this combo. One plan I considered was running more Backrow, and the Solemn Judgment in the side deck still seem good, especially vs DRNM, but I felt the combo loses to hand traps badly enough that Crossout was obligatory in the main.  Reprodocus has become the generic link 2 of choice, because it being a Dinosaur is relevant for some hands. I cut Giant Rex. In this combo-focused version it became another brick we couldn't afford. One notable thing about the deck is you can use Baroness to pop the Jurraegg token to summon Pankratops before you make the Herald. So you're using Baroness's pop to get an extra spell-speed 2 interruption.
Primary goal is to bring out the fusion monster. Build your way up through the subsets for powerful beaters, then fuse your Crimson Novas together to finish off your opponent.

deck_excerpt: Slap Arrival and Accesscode on the board, EZ win.
deck_description: I've been playing @Ignister online since GFTP came out and I've had a lot of fun playing the deck. It's mostly solved now so I felt like posting the decklist that I use. This deck has great ability to play through cards and can catch people off guard. The win condition is to make your opponent waste resources and then decimate them on turn 2. Sorry if the text is weird in some places, it won't let me put the names of the spells. @Ignister monsters - Bururu @Ignister (1) - Searchable by cyberse wicckid. Foolishes a card (usually your negate, or something to be revived by splash mage for a meet you only hand), then when used as synchro material you can special summon the other monster used as material. Very important for combo, but is searchable and doesn't help otherwise. Pikari @Ignister (3) - Starter, searches any AI spell or trap, which is incredibly useful. No reason not to play at 3. Plus it makes light dragon which is funny sometimes. Achichi @Ignister (3) - It's Stratos. Doyon @Ignister (3) - This card is absolutely nuts. When it's summoned, you can add 1 of your monsters from your grave to your hand, which is great for the field spell's gimmick. And that's not all - When it's sent to the graveyard as link material for a cyberse monster, you can add 1 of your A I. s/t from your graveyard to your hand. It's both achichi and pikari in one if your graveyard is loaded, which is why i play 3 and not 2. Drawing it is ALWAYS good. Danmari @Ignister (1) - banish from grave for HRDAA negate while you have arrival. Sent during combo. Gatchiri @Ignister (1) - Negate the effects of one Cyberse monster you control to special summon it. When it's sent to the graveyard, you can give your cards immunity. Nice for making safe plays, plus protects on board as well. Great for 8300 attack unaffected accesscode. Hiyari @Ignister (1) - Free special summon if you control an @Ignister monster, searches gatchiri by tributing one. Engine Spells - AI. Meet You (3)- LOCKS INTO CYBERSE EFFECTS! (Search by revealing an ED monster. Deals 2300 burn to you if you didn't special summon the monster you revealed). At 3 because you can still do combo off of starting with it. Ignister AILand - (3+Terraforming) The focus of the deck. Special summons a mon from hand while there's nothing in your MMZ. Can come back from graveyard by its effect. Cynet Mining - (3) More copies of starters. Can send combo pieces to GY sometimes. AIdle Reborn - (2) Is a quickplay monster reborn. Can use on opponent's turn and then link off doyon to use it again, going very high in card advantage. Also can be helpful to extend. AIContact - (0-1) Spicy draw 3 if you open an extra AILand. Can recycle it to go to the moon in card advantage. Extra Deck - Accesscode Talker(1) - I think you know why. The Arrival Cyberse @Ignister- (1) The big man. Transcode Talker (1)- Summons a link-3 or lower in your GY. Used on turn 2+ to go for a push Update Jammer (1)- Makes OTK with Accesscode Splash Mage (2) - Amazing card for cyberse, reborns any cyberse monster in defense position. Cyberse Wicckid (1) - I love this card. Searches a tuner when a monster is summoned in a zone it points to, and offers protection to itself and monsters it points to. Sometimes you just pass on this guy and call it a day. Dark Infant @Ignister (3) - Link 1, searches field spell. That's all you need to know. Fire Phoenix @Ignister (1) - This card is only there for Meet You, it's 2300 and fire. Dark Templar @Ignister (1) - Very important part of your combo, protect mr. soul charge at all costs. Link Spider (1) - Solid rocks brother. Turns nib into a cyberse. Light Dragon @Ignister (1) - Meet You, plus it can wipe a few cards off of your opponent's board. Wind Pegasus @Ignister (1) - Synchro monster for Bururu, plus if your arrival gets removed, your opponent's monster gets removed.   Everything else in the deck is flex spots. Your hand traps are important, as that is how you apply pressure with your Arrival Cyberse. Not hooked on crossout for this deck yet, as resolving combo doesn't mean instant win. I don't have combos on here right now, but you should be able to find the most important ones pretty easily. It's all for the same endboard anyways.

deck_excerpt: A Gouki Deck build for huge combos ending on multiple negates and a healthy sized hand
deck_description: So Gouki again. Ive been playing this Deck for quite a while now so heres how it works: Your general gameplan is to get 1x Gouki monster + at least 1 extender in hand.  You almost always want to normal summon your Gouki and then play further with your extenders like "War Rock Gactos" or "Fire Flint Lady" which guarantee you the Isolde. When you summon Isolde your Chaining is essential. You always want to use your Gouki, which you send for her summon, as Chain Link 1 and the Isolde as Chain Link 2.  For the searches you get of these two the optimal options are to add a "Gouki Headbatt" from the Gouki and whatever Gouki you used for Isoldes summon through the search you get of Isolde. We add the Gouki we used already by Isolde so we have a material for Headbatt, since he needs to discard a Gouki Monster to be special summoned. After this you wanna use Isolde to either get your "Gouki Twistcobra"(3 equip spells needed in Deck) ,"Gouki Octostretch" (1 equip spells needed in Deck) or "Gouki Guts" (1 equip spells needed in Deck). This should leave you with 3 Monsters on Board. The Isolde in the Extra Monster Zone, the Monster you summoned of Isolde and the headbatt you summoned trough its effect. Then you go into a Link 4 with these Monsters for the "Saryuja Skull Dread" and then add a Gouki Rematch to your hand. You'll use this rematch to summon back 2 Goukis (be carefull not to summon your Isolde target) and then start the codebreaker combo. This will give you enough materials for a Rusty and leave you with a Link-3 Monster as well. You'll use the Rusty to dumb the silent cloak and set the Shade Brigandine, the you activate the brigandine and banish the cloak to add a boots to hand which you can special to your side. You can then go into a Gryphon or an Apolusa (depending on if you fear the late Nibiru). IF you decide to go for Gryphon remember to first of: Add Phoenix Blade back to hand Seccondly: To use Brigandine for its Summon.  Then you can, if you have no more extenders, end your Turn by summoning a Verte Anaconda and using its effect to summon a Dragoon to your side (remember to summon it in a Zone where a Link monster Points to, if you Summoned a Gryphon) and banish the silent boots for a Fog Blade.  This is your basic bread and butter combo which will leave you with 2 Monster negates trough Apolousa, 1 trough Fog Blade and one Omni negate trough the Dragoon.  Of course, the Deck can play trough the multitude of engines, like the striker engine, in many different ways on your turn, based on of what you draw.  Here are a few combo specific plays:  If you draw Engage or Hornet Drones: You activate it to summon the token. Then you go into the Kagari to add back the Hornet drones, and reactivate it. Then you summon the Kaina by using the Kagari as Material for the Summon. Trough that you have a Link zone and a Warrior Monster. This gives you even with one extender enough room to do your combo or more.  War Rock Gacta : You have to normal summon a warrior to trigger his summoning condition. Thats about it  On another note: If you dont want to use Dragoon just play 3x War Rock Mountains instead of the Dragoon engine, since it searches you the Gacta which serves as an extender.  Pros of the Deck: Many options to get to your Combo pieces Space in the Extra Deck  Cons: Very Vulnerable to Handtraps and/or negates in general

deck_excerpt: The best bang for your buck. Decks in this category have the capacity to top premier events, though they're almost always supplemented with expensive
deck_description:
• Dragon Link is, as the name suggests, a Link-centric combo deck focused around Dragon cards. It has been a top-tier presence in the meta more or less consistently since mid-2020, and continues to adapt despite several banlist hits. On the October 2021 banlist, Dragon Link actually escaped completely unscathed, and was already considered a strong deck last format, so this deck remains a fantastic choice going forward.

  • The meta-relevant build often plays Chamber Dragonmaid alongside Dragonmaid Tidying for low-commitment and reliable disruption that also helps this deck grind turn 3 and onwards, while playing around board breakers like Dark Ruler No More. Chamber Dragonmaid is currently inaccessible to budget players, clocking in at over $70 apiece currently, but it is confirmed to get a reprint in the upcoming set Maximum Gold.

  • Mega-tins reprinted Chaos Ruler, a fantastic card in this deck that benefits basically all aspects of your game plan and enables you to synchro for Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss.

  • The trendy meta version of Dragon Link tends to play floodgates in the main or side deck. Both Rivalry of Warlords and Gozen Match have been seeing a ton of popularity lately, due to their strength against decks like Prank-Kids and Tri-Brigade even going second into an established board.

  • Since these floodgates are cheap, expect to see this bullet point repeated a lot for some other decks on this post.

  • DLink is one of the most adaptive decks in the game, and is getting both direct and indirect support in the upcoming sets. BODE has Dualwiel Dragon, enabling Rapid Trigger shenanigans to make Borreload Furious Dragon.

  • It also has Destroy Phoenix Enforcer, an extremely powerful fusion somewhat similar to Dragoon in how splashable it is into various decks, and Dragon Link is no exception.

  • In January, we will also see the Brave Token engine make a splash in Grand Creators, and it is possible to mix these cards with Dragon cards as well.

So my question was "Is Despia an improvement to Shaddolls?" The answer is mixed. The grind game is better, and the interruptions get real, but you hit Winda less consistently and while the ceiling is high the floor is very low. I think Pure or Invoked Shaddolls is probably better than this. Too bad, I was hoping I'd jive with these boss monsters, since they are Fiends, But I'm not sure this is better than just consistently making Winda, or even making Mechaba + Ecclesia with a chance to Winda. One nice thing about the deck is it doesn't care about Zombie World. Like at all. So, we're free to run the best floodgate in the format without the risk of blowing ourselves out.  So, for the Despia engine, I have 3 Aluber, 3 Tragedy, 1 Dramaturge, 1 Despia Theatre, and 3 Branded Opening. Aluber is your Stratos, and contributes to that great grind game and is a clear 3 of. I like 3 Tragedy because it helps consistently search my Despia cards, the grind effect on this is a little weak but it can set Branded Opening so that's useful. Dramaturge at 1 is fine, this is your big main deck boss monster, and represents a negate in a lot of situations as well, pretty good I'd say. For Shaddolls we have 2 Squamata, 1 Wendi, 1 Ariel, 3 each of the Fusions spells, and 1 each of the Traps. Small Package, the goal is actually to search these cards with Apkallone to make Shaddoll plays, but sometimes starting combos with Construct will be a better option than holding onto your Dogmatika card.  We run Super Poly, basically both archetypes are Super Poly archetypes, against Light and Dark monsters, Dark in particular, you can crack pretty hefty boards with absolute ease.  Dogmatika cards are cool, but oddly enough we're running 3 Nadir and basically 1 each of the cards it searches. That's it. A little sad, but this isn't an ecclesia deck, it just needs an easy way to send Apkallone for value.  Magicalized Fusion opens up Winda out of Verte Anaconda, which is cool and fun. Super cool and fun, super cool and fun. We run 2 Winda so we can back Winda up with Winda. I like Winda.  Droplets is Droplets, its just super good right now, and even though it sends for cost I think it is worth it. Solemn Strike is here because we need extra negates in the deck, and pretty badly.  The Side deck is little sloppy but overall I'm pretty happy with it. I probably won't work on this deck anymore, because I don't think I like this engine as much as Aleister or Magistus cards, even if they are Fiends.

deck_name: Magnet Warrior Deck - Post October 2021 Banlist
deck_description: Most people try using Magnet Warrior/Adamanciptors, some use Adamancipator/Fossils, and then we have those weirdos who use Magnet Warrior/Fossils.   What most people DON'T try, however, is putting these 3 forces together. By using the basic swarming and Special Summon material set-up of Magnet Warriors, the play extension and powerful abilities of Adamancipators and the brute force nature of Fossils, this deck is extremely versatile in terms of its aimed win conditions. (NOTE: This deck runs as little negation as possible, because 10 pounds of negation gets boring after some time.)   Crazy Specific 1 Turn Lockdown Mode (ends board with Cross-Sheep [Extra Monster Zone], Knightmare Gryphon [Linked to Cross-Sheep in the zone below it], and Cyberse Quantum Dragon [next to Cross-Sheep's Link]): Special Summon Researcher with its own effect, then activate Sentry's effect in GY to Special Summon itself. Activate Magnetic Field and use its effect to bring back Beta The Electro from the GY. Beta's effect on summon adds a Level 4 manila Magnet Warrior. Activate Researcher's effect, and Special Summon either a manila Magnet Warrior among the excavated cards or a Gamma The Electro. If you summon Gamma, use its effect on summon to Special the added Level 4 manila. Use the Level 4 manila to Link Summon Link Spider. Activate Super Team Buddy Force and target Link Spider to Special Trisbaena from GY so that it is co-linked to Link Spider. You can then Normal Summon any 1 monster from your hand (most likely the manila added with Beta's effect if Researcher Summoned a manila instead of a Gamma). Use the Normal Summoned monster and Trisbaena to Link Summon Knightmare Gryphon,who should be co-linked to Link Spider. (You can activate its effect on Summon if you want, but it's not really important to the lockdown.) Next use Beta and Link Spider to Link Summon Cross-Sheep above Gryphon's Link. Then tune Sentry with Researcher to Synchro Summon Quantum next to both Cross-Sheep and Gryphon's Links (for assurance). Cross-Sheep's effect on Quantum's Summon, giving all of your monsters +700 ATK. This board limits your opponent's ability to attack or use certain card effects (since only Quantum can be targeted and can boot bigger monsters back to the hand), restricts your opponent's Special Summoned monster effects (thanks to Gryphon), and not to mention the fact that you get 2 main beaters with 3200 ATK each.

To wash my pallete after building Despia Shaddoll, I wanted to build a purer (and more effective) version of Shaddolls. The idea is to spam Winda, back it with Mechaba, and abuse Nadir Servant to search your Shaddoll cards. The deck is a pile of broken spells and small engines.  For Shaddoll monsters, it is a small package, but not tiny, 3 each of the Squamata and Wendi, and 1 Ariel. You want to open Squamata or Wendi as often as possible to make the fusion spells live, and you need the 1 Ariel for the combos. It is also an incredible interruption. These are searchable off of Nadir Servant funnily enough. 3 of each of the Fusion spells, because we're a fusion deck and need to see fusion spells for the combos. They are both very good fusion spells. 1 of each trap because I wanted to keep the package just to essential cards.  3 Nadir Servant, 1 Ecclesia, 1 Fleurdelis. You don't usually summon Ecclesia, this is a generic Shaddoll searcher that also provides a Light monster for material. When you do summon Ecclesia she remains good. 1 of the Trap seems fine, you don't actually want to be locked out of follow-ups too often in your fusion deck.  1 Terraforming, 3 Meltdown, 3 Aleister, 2 Invocation. This helps give the deck another prong of attack in access to Invoked monsters and access to a good generic Fusion spell for making Shaddolls.  1 Magicalized Fusion, this is usually how you make your first Winda off Verte Anaconda. Guaranteed Windas are nice.  3 Super Poly. We're a little light on targets, but we're a Shaddoll deck, and this helps us make Shaddolls plays using monsters as materials at "Spell Speed 4".  3 Droplets. Should just be a steple right now if you want to play the game.  3 Secret Village of the Spellcasters. We play maindeck Spellcaster engines to get our cards back online, and we make Winda on our end board, so this is the first spicy floodgate we play.  In the Extra deck 2 Construct. You just need 1 for your turn 1 plays, we aren't a comboish version of the deck, we're trying to reliably make Winda a couple of times and Mechaba once. 2nd is for follow-up. 2 Winda, again I think this is needed for the grind game. 1 Apkallone, this is a negate to back up your plays sometimes, and a tool to send with Nadir Servant other times. 1 Titaniklad, this could come up in some hands but it isn't what we're playing Nadir for. 1 Nt'ss, this is to make the Trap card live. Starving Venom so Super Poly can break boards pretty well using your opponent's monsters. 1 of each Mechaba and Purgatrio. The best Invoked monsters, 1 for going first one for going second. For links we have 1 Artemis and 1 Almiraj. Artemis is important for turning Aleister into a LIGHT monster for Shaddoll plays but also makes him a low-end as a 1 card Mechaba you can run 7 of, and Almiraj means he just as easily accesses Purgatrio. Gravity Controller helps with your Construct combos that make guaranteed Windas. Cross-Sheep could come up in the grind game and be really useful there. Verte Anaconda is really insane in this deck, and necessary for certain opens into Winda 1.  For the side I started with Zombie World. In some matchups this will be better than Secret Village, even if it is worse in most, but it is relatively free in the deck, only impacting access to the Magistus Link 1, and having access to 2 broken floodgates for whichever is better in a matchup seems good. You could even run both going first against Dry, effectively 6 cards that shut down the ritual spell. I initially had the Solemns in the main deck, but I think they're a better side deck plan for this deck than a lot of the better options. We really lack negation, and being able to negate summons and effects could be a really important generic thing to do in matchups where our floodgates aren't effective. Then I threw in Droll and Lancea, high impact hand traps that are specifically good against the best 2 decks and gives us 6 cards to bring in in those respective matchups. Lancea is also good against Virtual World, which is probably the third best deck, and our floodgates are good against Dragon Link.

deck_excerpt: Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Heretic is everything this deck could've asked for.
deck_description:
Finally..After all this time. Dream Mirror, at long last..now they too can..MAKE VERTE! DUDUDUDUUUU (From here on out imagine Darude's Sandstorm frantically  playing in the backround) Dream Mirror has got to be one of the coolest archetypes ever created. They're creative, based on mythology, their artwork is fantastic and they absolute suck ass. You heard that right, Dream Mirror used to be a non linear deck with only 2+ card combos that most of the time resulted in a pop. But hey at least they looked cool. So before we're jumping in to what's changed for the Archetype let's take a detour at what this deck used to be.   Their origin story: But before we do that (we'll get there I promise) let's talk about their inspiration. Their original three Main Deck monsters, Ikelos, Morpheus and Phantasos were, according to greek mythology, siblings that each personified an aspect of dreams. Ikelos, or Phobetor is associated with Fright. Morpheus stands for Form and appears in dreams in the shape of a human and Phantasos stands for Fantasy. Together these three are called the Oneiri, the embodiment of Dreams. Or as a single character, Oneiros. If you haven't caught on yet, Oneiros is the archetypes boss monster in the form of a Fusion Card.   The Duality of Dreams: Each of these monsters comes in 2 forms, a Light and a Dark form, representing good and and bad dreams. There are also two field Spells, each representing one state of the dream. Every Dream Mirror monster (of these three) has the gimmick to tribute itself to summon their opposite form, if the opposite Field Spell is in a field zone (including your opponents). So if I control Ikelos, the Dream Mirror Sprite and a Dream Mirror of Terror I can then tribute Ikelos to summon Ikelos, the Dream Mirror Mara from deck. This can be done during either player's Main or Battle Phase. Each of them has an effect that triggers if they are summoned by the effect of a Dream Mirror monster. Sprite searches any Dream Mirror card, Mara Special Summons from hand, Friend Special Summons a Dream Mirror from the GY, Foe attack directly, White Knight protects itself and Black Knight destroys a card. Both Field Spells, Dream Mirror of Terror and Dream Mirror of Joy have minor effects, they are most needed for their names. Both of these have an effect that allows you to banish them during the End Phase to activate the opposite one directly from hand or deck.   Their strategy: The plan was usually to gain good advantage by swapping out your monsters during both player's turns. Sprite searches a monster which Mara Special Summons from hand. Usually a Friend that Special Summons from GY or a Black Knight to destroys a card. That way you could mass advantage while keeping disrupting your opponent (a little). Since you need both Field Spells to enable all of your monsters you would make use of Dream Mirror Hypnagogia. This would activate the Field Spells on both players fields, allowing every monster to use both their swap and their summon effect during either players turn.   Their fatal flaw: This is were we transition from a joyous dream of card advantage a to frightful nightmare of bricking. The only way to search Hypnagogia is through Sprite but Sprite doesn't trigger unless it is summoned by a Dream Mirror monster's effect. But you can't use their effects if you don't control the corresponding Field Spell. How's the Field Spell searched? Sprite but Sprite doesn't trigger unless - you see what I'm getting at? You need both a Field Spell and access to your monsters in order to start playing the game. You have the bare minimum in Dream Mirror Phantasms, which searches you a monster. Between that and One for One you had little means to access Sprite, which required Mara on Field and Dream Mirror of Joy in the Field Zone. And that's only what it takes to get to the cards to get your engine going. You then need to use their effects again to add, summon and do all the good stuff. There was no single card that did it all. You would brick a lot and then - obviously - would lose to any interruption. Oh and the Fusion Spell to summon your Boss Monster doesn't have Fusion in it's name either, which is fun. So you have a whole lot of cards you need to search off a single card and only little means to access that single card's effect.   Enter Sandmann 2021: BLVO came around and out of nowhere Konami decided to print legacy support for Dream Mirror. Like with every protagonist, their power spike is preceded by a Flashback. So they printed the baby version of their Boss monster and printed a new Boss monster altogether. The new addition to the main deck, Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Disciple could special summon itself, which was fine but didn't really address any of the issues the deck was facing. Sounds like they scrapped their archetypes theme but it's fantastically thematic. The old boss monster, Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Erlking was a LIGHT so they printed Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Tormentor who is a DARK, keeping the archetype not only on theme but completing them by giving every monster an opposite typing, but one... ---until now. It's the year 2021. It is October 7th and new legacy support is announced. The last remain Dream Mirror, the DARK version of our Boss Baby has finally been revealed and oh. my.   Am I dreaming? This card is pretty much everything this deck desperately needed. Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Heretic would on summon (yes, even on a simple Normal Summon, finally) search it's opposite, Disciple. Disciple's extend all of a sudden matters as Heretic can tribute another Dream Mirror (the Disciple) to not only Special Summon ANY Dream Mirror monster from your deck but also add the Field Spell necessary for its effect. This allows for a spicy new combo.   Time to make Verte: This is the new combo:
  1. Summon Heretic, add Disciple. Special Disciple
  2. Heretic tributes Disciple to summon Sprite and adds Terror. Activate Terror.
  3. Sprite, since it was Special Summoned by the effect of a Dream Mirror monster now searchs Dream Mirror of Chaos (The Fusion Spell)
  4. Link both off them away for Verte / Link Heretic off for Almiraj (if you play Accesscode this is another Attribute in the GY)
  5. Activate Chaos, banish both Neiroy from the GY to Fusion Summon Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Tormentor, which means a Monster effect negate on 5th summon so this combo is Nibiru-proof
  6. (Link Almiraj and Sprite into Verte, then) Activate Verte to summon Destiny HERO - Destroy Phoenix Enforcer
This is a monster effect negate, a targeted card destruction and two 3k ATK beaters on the field off a single card. It's not game breaking but it's actual modern Yu-Gi-Oh. In a Dream Mirror deck. Incredible.   What else? This is the combo off a single card. But if you open with a Dream Mirror monster besides Mara you can also use Sprite's other effect to summon Mara who will then summon the Dream Mirror monster from hand. Friend could then Special Summon another one from the GY. White Knight would equal another pop during your opponent's turn. If you open Hypnagogia or Chaos you can search the other to have both Field Spells live making your Dream Mirrors actually gain you advantage, too. Having Joy on the field also means that you can change from Tormentor into Erlking for another pop if you tribute another Dream Mirror monster. Dream Mirror Oneiromancy is another sweet pick-up off of Sprite if you open Chaos. It's a Spell/Trap or Special Summon negate. If you open with Destiny Fusion you can end on I:P Masquerena to make Apollousa during your opponent's turn. Depending on how you opened with you Dream Mirrors you might even be able to go into Underworld Goddess of the Closed World.   What's next? I dunno. I'm sure many cards in this deck will still change. Heretic completely changes how the deck plays (Not including Terraforming in Dream Mirror used to label you a heretic). Ratios need to be figured out. Maybe some names will be cut completely. There a few more Dream Mirror cards I haven't even included in the deck. This is but a first step in the right direction, a peek of what's to come. Maybe you wanna keep the ED simple and play Prosperity or Extravagance. Maybe you wanna lean into a r10nk OTK or play only Neiroy and Ikelos and play a bunch of handtraps. I don't know. And I love that I don't. This is gonna be interesting. So here you go: I welcome you to the world of Dream Mirror.

deck_excerpt: Just a semi-competitive penguin deck that can somehow go toe-to-toe against OP decks if you draw the right cards at the right time.
deck_description:
• Draw Magellanica, Sea Stealth Attack, Tornado Wall, Penguin Champion, and any monster in your deck.
  • Set Sea Stealth Attack and Tornado Wall then activate Magellanica. (note: if you draw Forgotten Ruin, it's okay. It's still an "Umi" card but you don't benefit from that card for synchro and xyz summon. Its effect is the same with Sea Stealth Attack but SSA is much better because it protects the backrow against spell/trap destruction cards.)
  • Set the other monster you drew to activate Penguin Champ's effect in which it summons itself to the field and you have an option to reduce its level. After it was special summon, activate Penguin Champ's effect of flipping the monster you set face-up. (note: If your set monster is Puny Penguin, you have an option to not adjust its level using Magellanica to summon Penguin Brave or adjust its level by 2 to summon White Aura Whale.)
  • During your opponent's turn, if he/she activates Twin Twister or Lightning Storm, activate SSA's effect to temporarily banish your synchro monster and protect your backrow. You also take no damage from direct attacks because of Tornado Wall. After that, your synchro monster returns to the field during the End Phase of your opponent's turn. You can also use SSA to save your monsters from card effects.
  • During your 2nd turn, once your synchro monster is on the field, you can attack twice if your synchro monster is WAW or attack once using Penguin Brave. (note: 1) If you draw Penguin Sword and the monster set by your P. Brave's effect was Nopenguin, flip Nopenguin before Penguin Brave attacks so that it would trigger Nopenguins effect that every time a penguin monster activate its effect of returning a card on hand, instead of going to the opponent's hand, it is remove from play. 2) If you draw Glacial Beast Polar Penguin this turn and Penguin Brave which you summon on your first turn set a monster on the field, flip the set monster to synchro summon either WAW or Graydle Dragon.)
  • The main deck have a lot of protection traps like Solemns, Aegis and Ice Dragon's Prison. (note: if your opponent uses Dragoon, bait him first by using any card effect so that he/she will use its once per turn negation effect then if you have a set Ice Dragon's Prison, activate it to banish 2 of his/her monsters including his/her Dragoon. If he/she is relying on the Predaplant Verte Anaconda to summon Dragoon, just negate its summoning or activation using Solemns.)
    • Update 10/10/21: To stop your opponent from summoning any OP cards like Dragoon, Zeus or Galaxy-Eyes Dragons, you need to have SSA, Tornado Wall and Magellanica/Forgotten Ruin face-up on the field and summon Barrier Statue of the Torrent. This stops your opponent from special summoning any OP monsters. If you're unlucky and your opponent summoned an OP monster, you can special summon 1 Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju on your opponent's field by tributing their OP monster.
    • To lock them out from special summoning any non-WATER attribute monster, normal summon Barrier Statue of the Torrent then tribute the OP monster your opponent have to special summon Gameciel. Every time your opponent attacks using Gameciel, you can use SSA's effect to temporarily banish your Barrier. You're opponent will not attack because of Tornado Wall because even your opponent attacks, you take no battle damage. Gameciel is also good if somehow your opponent uses Jinzo

deck_excerpt: S-Force Control with a pinch of Nemeses.
deck_description:
The Cards.
  • Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring ; Generally useful handtrap. Also a zombie :o
  • Nibiru ; Higher impact handtrap. Also a rock :o
  • Infinite Impermanence ; Another staple.
  • Called By The Grave ; The deck has a very clear chokepoint (Chiyomaru) that you *really* need to resolve. This might help...
  • Crossout Designator ; See above - also useful to stop people from Harpies'ing your backrow...
  • Reinforcement of the Army ; Searcher for Chiyomaru.
  • S-Force Bridgehead ; Archetype monster searcher. Usually to get a Chiyomaru or Gravitino into your hand. Protection effect rarely comes up.
  • Terraforming ; Searcher for Bridgehead
  • Pot of Prosperity ; Extra Deck isn't used much. Might as well add some sorely needed consistency.
  • S-Force Rappa Chiyomaru ; The S-Force starter. Get this into your hand ASAP.
  • S-Force Gravitino ; Great on-field effect and searches any S-Force card.
  • S-Force Pla-tina ; Pla-tina summoning a banished Gravitino is your main turn 1 combo.
  • S-Force Edge Razor ; Situationally useful field effect (Tri-Brigade Revolt...). Also helps with less than ideal opening hands where you have too many higher level S-Forces in hand. This is your main good way of getting enough materials for Justify... but is unfortunately Cyberse so Justify's unavailable with this under TCBOO.
  • S-Force Orrafist ; An extra piece of interaction that might be useful. Usually for if/when Chiyomaru resolves on my opponent's turn. Same Cyberse problem as above.
  • S-Force Dog Tag ; Helps set up another aligning column. Mainly a Gravitino target for when you already have Chase in hand.
  • S-Force Chase ; Your main piece of interaction. This is usually what you search with Gravitino.
  • Nemeses Flag ; Extra material to help summon Justify when you need it - or Eschatos. Return effect is also very useful for more drawn out games (acts a third Platina)
  • Archnemeses Eschatos ; Your main followup play - board wipe + lockdown against some decks.
  • S-Force Justify ; Your other followup option. A monster negate and very good at cleaning boards.
  • Dimensional Fissure ; Gets monsters banished for Pla-tina and Flag. Possibly annoying your opponent is a nice bonus :)
  • There Can Be Only One ; Strong floodgate card. You can play under this pretty much unhindered since all your monsters are different types (except Orrafist/Razor/Justify T_T)
  • Imperial Order ; Another strong floodgate.
  • The Extra Deck ; General utility cards and accesscode/topologics for finishers. If TCBOO is on the field and you need to summon a card that's already on the field - Knightmare Phoenix and Geonator Transverser could be good options that solve other problems too. Other than that - there's Dogmatika Maximus hate, Cyber Dragon hate and Waking the Dragon targets for when your opponent is too eager to destroy your backrow.
The Strategy.
  1. You want to go first. The ideal opening hand has Chiyomaru and Gravitino. Summon Chiyomaru -> Banish Gravitino -> Summon Platina -> Revive Gravitino -> Search Chase.
  2. If you Chiyomaru, Gravitino and Platina in hand: You can summon Edge Razor from Chiyomaru to summon Platina from hand instead. This gives you one more monster, one more Chase bounce, one more field column effect.
  3. If you have the above combos and a Chase already in hand, you usually search Bridgehead or Dog Tag depending on whether or not Bridgehead is already activated. Dog Tag gives an extra column aligner/body for Chase bounce. Bridgehead could search Dog Tag or be used next turn if already activated this turn for followup.
  4. When everything goes wrong and Chiyomaru gets negated: Try to use Chiyomaru on your opponent's turn to either align Gravitino with an important monster to break their combo or summon Orrafist to maybe destroy 1 monster.
  5. If you manage to survive your opponent's turn: Justify or Eschatos might swing the game back in your favour. Justify requiring exactly 3 materials can be difficult - usually a mix of Edge Razor, Platina, Flag are needed. Eschatos is much easier to summon (between your handtraps and your destroyed monsters you should have enough different types) but you need to draw into either it or Flag.
  6. Hope your opponent doesn't read...
