deck_excerpt: Earthbound Immortal Wiraqocha Rasca for the grind game
deck_description: Version 3.0. Running an interaction suite which is better defensively, and fewer floodgates, and well as less confliction with D. Shifter. So, I'm on all 6 pots. Flunders doesn't really special summon, doesn't use the extra deck as a result, and only draws a few cards. You're also highly reliant on seeing Robina or Map + Flunder. Digging deeper into the deck just improves consistency a lot. I think you should be running at least 5 of these, they don't even conflict. I'd avoid adding Extravagence into the mix, and I think it is worse than Prosperity in this deck, because you need to see such specific starter cards to get your game on. I'm trying 1 Gold Sarc, which helps you chain block and subs in for the field spell in some but not all of your combos. Then Terraforming and all 3 of the field spell. This version is built around being able to play an Earthbound Immortal card, so you need the field spell, and it also creates a bunch of two card combos, so I think it is actually a fine consistency card in its own right. Unknown Wind is actually a grind game card. Being able to tribute an opponent's cards, including spells and traps, is pretty huge, and so is the ability to put 2 random Flunders back into your deck to draw 2. For Flunder monsters, the package is getting larger. 3 Robina is obligatory, it is 1 card combo. 3 Eaglen makes a lot of sense, since this way we are running 8 Flunder names for Map and Gold Sarc to start your plays, and Eaglen is the second to best Flunder. 1 of each Toccan and Strich. Both are needed for the Rasca combo that hand loops the opponent for 3, one represents some extra disruption, the other drastically improves your grind game. We also run 1 of the trap. The trap is bomb, but you search it with the combo and reset it with either Raiza or Toccan, so you can recycle a single copy of the trap turn after turn with Razia and Rasca. For boss monsters, Empen is a decent flood gate and our main beat stick, and also searches out cards, usually the field spell or the trap. Raiza is a great piece of disruption that has the valuable upside of resetting cards from your GY to the top of your deck. Rasca hand loops opponents, usually for 2 on your turn 2 or occasionally for 3 on the opponent's turn 1 going first, and also recycles the Raiza by shuffling it back into the deck for later use. 5 floodgates are good enough, to avoid them conflicting too much. These are cards that can just randomly win you games when your combo gets disrupted effectively. Lose 1 Turn is pretty amazing, a 1 turn Skill Drain for Special Summoned monster which our deck doesn't make anyways that can buy you a lot of time. I cut Skill Drain, it conflicts with the deck's gameplan too much to be truly effective, you never wanted to flip it up until you were losing anyways. Imperial Order, on the other hand, is the tits, for sure makes the cut. Macro Cosmos and Dimensional Fissure can conflict a little bit, but will generally hit opposing cards much higher and are mostly free, and hit other decks really hard. Dimension Shifter is the other 3 copies of this style effect, on a hand trap. You can reset it with Raiza, so it is basically Macro Cosmos if you see it. Book of Moon is already a great offensive card, but in this deck is also doubles as a defensive card, since you can chain block with banished Flunders to screw Ash and book your Eaglen to protect from Imperm and Veiler, and you don't really lose to other common hand traps. It is also run because it doesn't conflict with D Shifter. Imperm same shit different pile, weird that it is worse than Book of Moon in this deck but there it is. Extra Deck is a Zeus package and then Prom Thrush. You shouldn't often need to go into the extra deck, but being able to make Zeus instead of your normal summons will sometimes come up so you may as well run it. The rest doesn't matter, Ultimate Falcon is a mascot, the Knightmares into Accesscode is an option for cleaning up and Shuraig is for the Dogmatika matchup, free search if they're bad and hit your extra deck. Combos Robina Combo Normal Robina Robina effect, add Eaglen, summon Eaglen Eaglen effect, add Empen tribute summon Empen Robina and/or Eaglen's effects chain block Empen. Add them to the hand. Empen effect, add City of Dreams to your hand. Now on your opponents turn you can continue the combo with City of Dreams, either making Raiza or Barrier Statue. Raiza can even pick up the Trap if it is banished. If you already have the Eaglen you can add the Barrier Statue and summon it out with the Empen on your turn. Same if you just see the Barrier Statue. If you see Raiza or the Empen you can use the second Empen to search the continuous spell before tributing it to the Raiza. On a good turn you can get the Barrier statue and a search / reset of the trap while removing 2 cards off of the Raiza. 3 if you already have the continuous spell. Cut Called. It's a great card, but too redundant with the other banishing effects. In its place I'm running 1 Gold Sarc, which is effectively the Field Spell for most of your combos and lets you chain block. Robina + Toccan combo This one can also be done with Robina + Map, but I'm going to go through this one because this is the backwards way into the Earthbound Immortal card. Normal Robina Robina effect, add Eaglen, summon Eaglen Eaglen effect, add Empen, tribute summon Empen Empen cl1, Robina cl2, Eaglen cl3 recover Robina, add Map (DON'T SUMMON) Play Map. Map effect, banish the trap, summon Toccan, grab the trap. Ending your turn on Empen + Toccan. On your opponent's main phase, activate the trap. Summon Robina, which grabs Strich, summons Strich which banishes a card (your own trap, for example) and summons Eaglen, which adds Earthbound Immortal. Earthbound Immortal tributes over Robina and Eaglen, adding them back to the hand while chainblocking its effect, shuffling itself and the lesser Flunders back into the deck to make your opponent randomly discard 3 cards. You also still have Empen. You more commonly see this play through map + Robina, which is mostly similar but you can use Toccan to loop the trap. I like this version of the deck because it has so many ways to grind, with Rosca shuffling your monsters back into the deck, Toccan and Raiza resetting the trap for additional use, with the Raiza combo you can search out the spell to grind with Apex Avian, and you can afford to run high-powered floodgates to stall your opponent out even if your combos are interrupted. This also makes it a non-linear deck, in that the same 2 cards can result in multiple different end boards, Empen + 1 of your other plans. The Rosca combo is nice because it doesn't really incorporate any bricks - you have to play Toccan, Strich, and Map if you go for this combo, but most lists are playing these cards anyways, and the only real "brick" is the Rosca itself, and what drew me to the Rosca was that I wanted to run 1 more boss monster for the grind anyways. In some sophisticated board states Rosca even lets you reset the Raiza to use it again, the card is actually reasonably in the grind, plus I think on average if you have the choice of setting up Barrier Statue, searching a second time with Empen before hitting an opponent with Raiza, or hand looping them for 3, the hand loop option is probably the best of these. This is especially true if you have the continuous spell or search it because you have the trap, enabling you to make Rosca into a 3100 ATK beatstick that can attack directly while tributing an opponent's monsters and hand looping them for 3. I think that the loop that you should usually be doing with Rasca isn't to hand loop them for 3 on their turn on the first turn cycles. I think you should be aiming the end on Empen + Barrier Statue, using Raiza to shut down their normal summon while resetting a card, then using Rasca to hand loop them for 2 on their turn to reset the Raiza. Used properly this strategy can theoretically grind for as many turns as your opponent has 2 cards in their hand, and it eats up their resources while resetting theirs. But you might be inclined, depending on the matchup, to favour Rasca opens if pure raw cards are a problem. There will be other matchups, usually Trap based decks, where Raiza plays are necessary anyway, so being able to use one copy of Raiza multiple times is pretty appealing.   Cheat sheet for combos Robina = Empen + trap (Represents Raiza for disruption, Statue for a floodgate, or Apex Avian for a negate) Robina + Map, OR Eaglen + Map, OR Toccan + Map, OR Robina + Eaglen, OR Robina + Toccan = Empen + trap into hand loop Robina + Eaglen, OR Robina + Map, OR Eaglen + Map, OR Robina + Barrier Statue = Empen + Barrier statue + Trap Robina + Raiza, OR Robina + Empen = Empen + Trap into Empen search into Raiza   Ways to grind Return Apex Avian into the hand, and use the continuous spell to put back whatever you need to search to get your game going while drawing cards. Summ0n Barrier Statue, Raiza their normal summon to reset the trap, use Wiraqocha Rasca to rinse and repeat while hand looping them. Use Toccan to loop back the trap and your Empens to always have a summon and a monster Use Raiza to loop back D. Shifter to always have D. Shifter, use Toccan to loop back the trap Just go through your bosses one by one as they are answered. That's before we get to the games you auto-win with your floodgates.

deck_excerpt: endymion flexing with power and potential.
deck_description: i have recently started playing around with endymion, it does feel like a complicated deck deck to all the text, but it is one where you can run a number of engines  in does work well with mythical beast, generating lots of spell counter to give me draw power, search power or to blow up the board.  start with your spell counter bank, this could be the field spell Magical Citadel of Endymion, Magister of Endymion, Servant of Endymion, Reflection of Endymion and Magical Abductor, or a mythical beast that you managed to special summon, using mythical beast jackal king. mythical institution, make a good middle ground.  your search are servant of endymion (special summons itself and a spell counter monster from deck), magical abductor (searches any spellcaster master from 3 spell counter), mythical institution (searches any spellcaster at the cost of spell counter equal to it level), mythical beast master cereberus (search any mythical beast monster).  draw engine is spellbook with blue boy, and spellbook of knowledge, from later game drawing the field card is added but is a flex card. another draw engine is sky striker, i original ran instead of red-eyes dark dragoon. yes red-eyes dragoon is not need to break board but i got fed up to losing to it. i did run accesscode talker, because i don't own the card but left it in the side deck option, the sky striker engine is a flex spot as it gives you access to powerful cards like widow anchor (to negate and steal monsters), afterburner (surgically breaker baord and backrow) and shark cannon (to disrupt graveyard plays), not to mention thin out the deck and give accesscode talker more material to work with.  red-eyes package because red-eyes dragoon is a thing and is to be feared or play around.  all the any card are a self explanatory, chronograph sorcerer, is a free monster on the field, grabbing timegazer from deck, special summoning itself and another speelcaster when i spellcaster is destroyed, great high scale at 8 and at level 6 easy to pendulum summon. it value increase once odd-eyes vortex is on the field as you can send timegazer back to the deck for an omni negate.  pendulum treasure is a foolish for pendulum, is you drop a mythical beast, you can use mythical beast bashilisk to put in back in deck and draw, jackal, is an low cost search  for mythical instution, but is a plus in generating spell counter, garuda is backrow removal if needed, but can also bounce special monster back at the cost of 3 spellcounter, great for disruption, i wish i could run more, so any extra is a side deck option.  instant fusion, i have choose to flex with thousand eyes and millennium eye, millennium is a definite one of thousand not so much and would be my replacement for accesscode. i just like to fact i can steal an opponent monster and link it off.  in the extra deck as mention a lot depend on how you want to play and whether you have the cards or not, day-breaker is a flex spot and can be sub out for any link-2 as can abomination unchained, if accesscode is your thing then borrelsword, is also flex. i did sometime wish i had more then one selene but by then i have set a board and just want to extend more.  going first i usually end with apollousa with 3 to 4 negates with endymion the master himself, or 2 negate with endymion, and mythical beast king.  going second i have been a break board and playthrough about 2-3 disruptions, handtraps or otherwise.  i have not tried this build with handtrap, but i image you can run dimension shifter, as you don't need your graveyard, if you have your scale and field spell, selene would still get 3 spell counter and can summon from hand.  macro or dimersional prison, mystic mine and secret village can all fit in this deck as floodgate to establish the board or to stop opponent from playing.  hope you have fun.

Hello there, this is a fun Windwitch deck I have been working on lately. It contains a little Charmer engine, to facilitate followup after you set up your first turn board and to increase the consistency of the deck. Windwitches I don't have too much to say about the Windwitches. They have a one card combo, ending on an indestructible Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon. Except for Windwitch - Ice Bell, that enables said combo, Windwitch - Glass Bell has a important role in this build, duo to its 1500 def and its ability to search for any Windwitch monster. Charmer engine The engine is build out of three cards: Wynn the Wind Channeler, Spirit Charmers and Possessed Partnerships. Wynn the Wind Channeler is a card played in many wind-based decks, thanks to its searching ability. It searches Windwitch - Ice Bell for the cost of discarding itself and another wind monster. It is also treated as a Charmer card, so it is searchable of off Spirit Charmers. Spirit Charmers is the heart of the engine. It effectively increases your ability to search for Windwitch - Ice Bell and on top of that sets up a play for turn three, by setting Possessed Partnerships to the field. Possessed Partnerships allows you to special Windwitch - Glass Bell from grave. It is a searchable Back to the Front so to say. Special summoning Windwitch - Glass Bell during your opponent's end phase allows for Accescode plays or for level 8 and level 7 synchro plays during your turn, without being locked into wind monsters.   The rest of the deck are just staples like crossout which help you to play through handraps or negate the activation of cards like Dark Ruler No More.   I like the deck for all the tiny interactions between both the Chamers and the Witches. The side deck presents some accountable options, but can be customized at will. Suggestions to improve the deck are welcome. :) Have a nice day, everyone!

deck_excerpt: I still don’t know how I did this, but I guess I got first place at a competitive locals with the list here
deck_description: So… today I was at a locals with budget mathmechs. And well… I got first place and went undefeated so yeah, let’s just say today was a good day, and I’m not talking pushovers either by the way, I’m talking 3 games vs fullpowered top decks.  The tournament was small and there weren’t a lot of people but I feel very proud of myself regardless.  Round one: mathmechs vs Dlink  So I matched into a Dlink player  Game one his entire opening was just HTs, I closed the game after negating a striker dragon and ending his turn  Game two I got clapped because I ran out of resources  Game three, went into time, I had much more lp so I got the W  Round two: mathmechs vs (maybe dogma?) invoked  Game one my opponent opts first and ns alister “search invo- “ I dropped my effect veiler so he just went into secure guardna pass, some shenanigans later he eventually got his turn again, draws, summons albaz fuses away my poor magma and gets titankind, attacks a clock spartoi and then I showed him his mistake, bullionblade was equipped and I milled devision and overpowered the titankind, next turn I set up and attack for game.  Game two, He opts first again, ns alister, I just drop another effect veiler, lol. My turn I do shenanigans but was hit by about 3 handtraps and decided to land on linkuriboh and magma. Ns albaz? What if… second effect veiler? I swear it alway gets into my hand, I final sigmaed him for game  Round 3: mathmechs vs Tri-Brigade  Game one I run into a billion handtraps but eventually get game when I realized he didn’t have summon to use  Game two a rescue cat took an effect veiler and then I attack for game with final sigma, it was an interesting game to say the least  But yeah, that was the tournament for me, I went 3-0 and got first place with mathmechs.  And that bought a question to mind for me: am I just that godly?

deck_excerpt: Ghostrick deck based on the new support that is being released!
deck_description: I tried making the Ghostrick archetype as fast as possible but it lacks heavily on first turn as it needs to set a monster to start any plays, Ghostrick Shot and Parallel Exceed are the best cards to see first turn as they allow you to start going into your xyz monsters first turn to add specific Ghostrick cards and establishing a board, going second is even more of a challenge to overcome as setting against your opponents board is likely to end poorly. Most of the Ghostrick traps are played at 1 copy mainly for the reason they will brick your hands and are only strong when you have established, however it shouldn't be an issue because almost all the xyz monsters for the Ghostrick archtype can get a Ghostrick card back when they are sent to the graveyard.  You can run mystic mine as a very strong option to control the board and allow you to set up your plays but it was not included in this deck list because I don't enjoy playing the card.  The side deck here is just to reflect cards that can be added instead of other cards in the main deck as they are all strong options.

deck_excerpt: I've got hooked to gizmek unique mechanics lately (◕‿◕)
deck_description: Interrupted Kaiju Slumber + Gizmek Uka = Barrier statue (the water one, the wind statue you only gonna use against water decks); basically this is the combo and can branch to a XYZ Rikka if you chain Orochi and Uka special summons. You can do this combo in the first turn but you would need to have at least one monster to active Kaiju Slumber then proceed like normal. Normally you will not be able to use this in the first or second turn since kaiju Slumber is unsearchable, so the deck has a control layer that together with the kaijus helps to stall time.  The new card New Clear World is very good and indeed, can do a good par with Uka but not as good like Kaiju Slumber, because to use Clear Wolrd you would need at least 4 specific cards. Would be: Summon a kaiju using the enemy monster ~summon any monster in your field ~activate New World to bring any monster from the deck ~Special summon Uka ~with Uka summon a barrier statue. You not only can't do this in the fist turn but also have to do all of this while counting in not being negated and having a perfect hand, unlikely to ever happen. But ngl that new spell will be at 3 in many self-destructive decks and in these that uses alot of diferent types as Prank kids or Invoked.  In my last deck i explains Uka effects but feel free to read the card if you still don't know its potential.  Took off Dogmatika because i wanted to see how would the deck perform in 40 cards and discovered that is better this way.  I'll probably not update this deck anymore unless i found some broken shit since i think the deck is as it is now.  Go second.     Almost forget! If you are against a water deck you lose! Since going against water means using the wind statue and giving to you opponent Gadarla that you can't beat :), and because you can't rely upon Luna which have only two copies. But if you are not playing singles you can in the second duel exchange Gameciel and water statue for Dogoran and a fire statue.     Sorry for any grammar mistakes.  Any suggestions are welcome.  GLHF

deck_excerpt: A ghost from the past comes to kick your ass
deck_description: Perfect circle was an old deck from the end of the GX era, this deck aimed to use HERO cards to draw and facilitate tributes for cards like Raiza The Storm Monarch as well as Light And Darkness Dragon. Only one of these cards is really playable today and that would be LADD, which just so happen to synergize with a few of the new HERO cards coming in BODE, fusion destiny can enable DPE plus the needed tribute fodder for LADD, these two cards work beautifully together, DPE can pop LADD after you have run out of negates to trigger the second effect of LADD to blow up your board to resurrect a monster from grave, which in turn triggers DPE's effect to summon a destiny HERO during your standby phase. The deck can also play like normal HERO if the more gimmicky game plan fails. I think this is a neat deck, not good per say, but neat.

deck_excerpt: Borreload Savage Dragon + Herald of the Arc light + Elemental Hero Plasma = Win.
deck_description: I will uptadate this deck tomorrow with all information about it.  I sleep.  !uptadate: this deck is about making a big board with deskbot 001 and the gizmek cards are in the support role.  The one card combo: Normal summon Deskbot 003 ~003 special summon a Deskbot 001 ~using these two link summon Crystron ~Crystron special summon another 001 ~link summon Auroradon ~Auroradon will summon his tokens ~after the token been summoned Chain the two Deskbot 001 effects and special summon them ~using one of the 001 and a token Syncro summon a Cupid Pitch and dont forget to rise its level ~syncro summon Borreload Savage Dragon usin Cupid Pitch plus one token ~Cupid effect will activate and add Plasma from your deck ~now activate Auroradon effect that tribute 2 to special summon Coltwing from the deck ~Coltwing summon more 2 tokens and deskbot 001 summon itself again ~using 001 and a token summon Herald of the Arc Light in defense position ~tribute 3 phantom beast to special summon Plasma from your hand. The final board shall have 2 negates and 1 skill drain in monster form (Plasma).  If you use the field spell before starting your combo, in the end you'll have 7-8 counter, so you dont have to worry in hindering your own negates.  Gizmeks have facility to special summon, so even if you dont get Deskbot 003 is still possible to combo.  One Darkruler no More or Forbidden droplet can make your board useless so i added Solemn Judgment to negate these spells.  When using pot of prosperity NEVER banish a combo piece.  That's all thanks for reading.  GLHF

deck_excerpt: An altered Marincess deck! Use the diverse array of water attribute cards in this deck to cool down your hard hitting Cyberse Link monsters!
deck_description: Altered Marincess deck with a full Link card extra deck. Based on mixing my favorite attribute (Water), with my favorite card type (Link), as well as my favorite species (Cyberse) . I was lucky the Marincess archetype existed, as without it these 3 concepts would not gel smoothly at all. The strategy for this deck is simple, Marincess Marbled Rock is your ace monster, use either her or Marincess Great Bubble Reef and ramp their power using the effect monsters in the deck such as Marincess Star Fish! Most of your high in monsters have solid defense provided from the trap cards as well as some of the other Link Marincess girls providing a nice shield from card effects and battle damage. You may be wondering about Relinquished Anima, and to be honest, I just like him :) use the DeepSea MacroTrema to get him on the field and be mean! Any other cards that may seem out of place are used to either ramp your more efficient cards, or are used in a specific way to effect combat specific situations (Like ShootingCode Talker). All in all this deck was made for me to have fun with! I hope you can appreciate this deck as much as I do!

deck_excerpt: Current version of The Agent of Force Mars LP Gain OTK
deck_description: Current version of The Agent of Force Mars OTK Tell me if you have any idea how to improve consistency and anti-meta nature of the deck The strategy is to gain as much LP as possible from your opponent's plays, gaining advantage from the LP gained, and to OTK with Mars   Main deck: The Agent of Force - Mars is unaffected by spell cards and can't be ashed. It gains ATK equal to the positive difference of LP between you and your opponent when The Sanctuary in the Sky is on the field Nova Summoner and The Agent of Mystery - Earth (tuner of the deck) are bodies and searchers for The Agent of Force - Mars Zeradias, Herald of Heaven is a good level 4 Fairy monster and a searcher for The Sanctuary in the Sky The 2 Performapal Kuribohble and the 1 Checksum Dragon works as the three battle faders with the advantage of making you gain LP The Agent of Life - Neptune and Master Hyperion are plan B. The first allowing you to special summon Mars from graveyard if necessary and the latter being an easily summonable beatstick with a destruction effect Ghost sister & spooky dogwood and Child's play are the two best LP gain card under normal playing conditions (which isnt the case of Soul Absorption) The Sanctuary of Parsath works as a clone of The Sanctuary in the Sky to increase the probability of Mars having his attack boost Gingebread House is a tech card that allows you to get rid of your opponent's monsters that have more than 2500ATK while gaining 500LP for each monster destroyed. Its a bit slow and risky, so it has been replaced by a 2nd Mystic Mine to stall if you dont have The Sanctuary in the Sky Divine Punishment is a type specific solemn to save your monsters Dried Winds is a continuous trap that allows you to destroy a monster every time you gain LP Rainbow life is the best LP gain trap card, which can be activated in any players turn, can be chained to its destruction, and is effective the whole turn its activated to convert monsters attacks into LP gains   Extra deck: Dispatchparazzi is a Link 2 that allows you to redirect all attack to it, thus saving a monster of choice, while gaining half of the attacking monster's ATK as LPs. Sweet Majoram is a Dried Winds searcher as well as a Dried Winds on legs, allowing you to destroy a monster every turn in which you gain LP. Ancient Sacred Wyvern is the synchro version of Mars, non-dependant on a field spell, with a 2100 base attack that can be revived by paying 1000LP. Colossal Fighter works in a loop with Rainbow life to make you gain any amount of LP you want if it attacks a monster with higher ATK than itself as it revives at will. Celestial Knightlord Parsarth is a link 3 that can search every card with "The Sanctuary in the Sky" in its text.

deck_excerpt: This deck can combo off first turn off of two cards and make a ridiculous board OR break almost any board with super poly.
deck_description: Step 1: All you need to do the combo is Ready Fusion and any normal summonable monster. Step 2: You must special summon Allvain the Essence of Vanity and normal summon a monster. Step 2: Link summon Crystron Halqifibrax and activate its effect. Step 3: Summon Deskbot 001 from deck using Halqifibrax effect. Step 4: Make Mecha Phantom Beast Auroradon +3 tokens and Summon Deskbot 001 using it's effect. Step 4: Synchro summon Shooting Riser Dragon using 2 tokens and Deskbot 001. With Shooting riser's effect you must send a level 2 monster to the grave for the next step of the combo. (Ex: PSY-framegear Gamma). Step 5: Synchro Summon Chaos Ruler, the Chaotic Magical Dragon and PROFIT. The combo can continue in many paths from here but for the sake of efficiency I will end it here. Notes: Use Branded Opening only after you exhausted all your other combo options, because it locks you out of summoning anything but Fusions. When Branded in Red is used in conjunction with Guardian Chimera it is a devastating combo.

deck_description: This deck is meant to allow players to use the incredibly nostalgic Summoned Skull archfiend archetype while still pulling off newer combos using the Red Archfiend Dragon synchro monsters. The goal is either to combo out one of the Red Dragon Archfiend monsters turn one and wipe your opponent's board or to play a slower control style continuously bringing back Summoned Skull until your opponent has run out of options. This deck is NOT meant for the meta but is fun to play against other nostalgic or casual decks.

This deck is the perfect exemple that pendulum isn't broken and is the perfect exemple that any deck that can make Verte is good.  Anyways, i tried my best to make metalfoes can go against MORE decks, thats why i ain't using Super Polymerization because even if it make a good Synergy it's not good enough.  Just a combo idea:  Normal summon Rescue Rabbit ~Activate Rescue Rabbit and summon any normal monster ~link summon 2 link spiders using the normal monsters ~Verte Anaconda.  This can be done in various ways since it's a pendulum archtype.  The ideal first turn board (and the best i could think) is having a dragoon, Alkahest, 1 Fullmetalfoes Fusion and 1 "Metalfoes" monster. deck_excerpt: A mid-range rouge deck that can set up a combo with Dragunity and try and out grind opponents with Dragonmaids.
deck_description: This deck functions as 2 engines that synergise well together and are held up by a good selection of staples for the current metagame (post 21 mega-tin, pre BODE).  The Dragunity engine seeks to set up a turn one play using Dragunity Remus and a discard to end on a Hieratic Seals of Heavenly Spheres and either Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon or Borreload Savage Dragon. This leaves you with a normal summon, and 4 cards in hand. The Dragonmaid engine is what really wins grind games. After the Dragunity engine has performed its combo you can normal summon either Chamber or Parlor Dragonmaid, the search or send Dragonmaid Changeover (the fusion spell). This paired with the Dragon Ravine left in hand after the combo you can send Dragunity Arma Gram and use his graveyard effect to special summon himself, allows you to fusion summon Dragonmaid Sheou.

Dragoon is still legal, and Necrovalley hits 2 of the top 3 decks really hard, so now is a good time to be on the Gravekeeper's engine in a stun deck. The deck is basically a pile of cards that search Necrovalley, a pile of cards that make Dragoon, some Pots, some Traps, and 3 copies of Royal Tribute. The game plan is simple, you establish Necrovalley + Dragoon and hope that it is enough to deal with everything they've got, and maybe occasionally Royal Tribute them.  So, 3 Necrovalley and a Terraforming seems obligatory. Necrovalley is the whole point of this deck, and you really want to maximize naturally drawing this card over searching it, and Terraforming remains the best way to search it. 3 Gravekeeper's Commandant seems like overkill but I want to try it out at 3 before trimming it back - it is effectively more copies of Necrovalley, which could be redundant run in these numbers but helps ensure you actually see Necrovalley. Necrovalley Throne searches for Commandant to find you Necrovalley, but I like this card more because it also searches for Headman for access to Dragoon, meaning seeing this alongside Commandant makes Necrovalley + Dragoon boards. 1 Headman to enable this. We're on 3 Red-Eyes Fusion and 3 Red-Eyes Insight to search Red-Eyes Fusion, with the bricks these entail. These are for easy access to Dragoon, which protects Necrovalley and is hard to out and a source of pressure, all at the same time. This card is stupid. We have 3 Royal Tribute. These can be a defensive card if you already have Necrovalley, but are mostly an offensive card to just shut opponents down by destroying all of their starters. 3 Droplets, these should just be a staple in most deck lists this format, even though we run low monster count this card is still just incredible. 3 Pot of Extravagence. You need card advantage in this deck, and you need to eat up those Ash Blossoms, as not a lot else stops your deck, but Ash really does hit both sides of the trick. 1 Called By the Grave, another way to eat up those Ashes, I'd make space for 3 if I could. 3 Torrential Tribute with 1 Fury to search it. This card doesn't pop Dragoon and combined with Solemn Strike will eat up whole combo boards, and is really powerful, so even though the spell telegraphs it I thought 4 in the main was a good idea. Lastly, I'm on the Solemn brigade, 3 Judgment and 3 Strike. Strike is really good alongside Dragoon or Torrential Tribute, and is just generically good going first or going second. I wanted some Judgment in the 55 for games 2 and 3 when the disruption comes in, but I'd prefer to main the card and side cards that are more impactful in specific matchups or circumstances. The card is amazing going first and still pretty good going second, and is a great generic answer to most sources of pressure an opponent can apply.  So, working through some probabilities, I discovered the deck has just under a 75% chance of making Dragoon and just over a 75% chance to make Necrovalley. This is pretty good all things considered, but it did change my attitude about Pot of Prosperity. You'll only get both on the field in about 50% of your games without it, but it improves your odds of making both greatly by standing in for either, digging 6 cards deeper into your deck. The maths started to get way above my head for just a children's card game, but you should see Necrovalley + Dragoon in over half of your games without Prosperity, and Prosperity should theoretically improve your odds of making both together, with 6 cards and several 2 card combos standing in for Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon, and 9 cards total representing Necrovalley. The reason I'm off Terraforming is running the 1 Terraforming seems a little too redundant while not actually improving our final odds by that much, and Commandant represents part of a 2 card combo to make Necrovalley + Dragoon. The other adjustment is running copies of Needle Ceiling to represent more Torrentials without giving up the game.  Nope, I was wrong. Extravagence is better in this deck. You need raw cards for Dragoon and you're consistent enough in seeing Necrogoon before the Prosperity. In every test hand I saw it Extravagence was comparable or straight better. Extravagence is still a decent consistency boost in a deck with such high odds of seeing your players, and it plays well with traps and Dragoon.

deck_excerpt: So, this deck attacks the game from like 4 different angles, and that's kind of cool.
deck_description: Fish engine maybe? It's hard finding 1 card engines with consistency cards, few bricks, and little conflicting with Necrovalley, but Toad is a card.  So, the list started with me thinking that Necrovalley is pretty good right now, we're in a format where two of the top decks are kind of in a league of their own, and Necrovalley is very disruptive to both of them, especially Drytron. It's also such an appealing engine to run, because you have so many copies of Necrovalley. Since it is good right now it has an edge over other field spell floodgates. However, Necrogoon is a little bit linear and relies a lot on Dragoon. Sure it usually puts up a Dragoon, but 1 negate + Necrovalley seems a little easy to out, provided people are prepared for a meta with Dragoon in it.  Dogmatika was the easy alternative engine to pair with it. Getting an interruption or three off of easy cards and searching backrow works well with the plan of Royal Tribute and traps, and there is no conflict with Necrovalley. The Fish part came in later in deckbuilding - I was basically looking for a 7 card engine, 3 starters 3 consistency cards and a brick, that could summon from the Extra Deck for Ecclesia, and worked under Necrovalley or at least could play around it being on the table. Invoked was the first thing I tested, but I found the engines conflicted too much to make Mechaba reliable. Destiny Hero would be appealing, save that Phoenix Enforcer can't revive itself under Necrovalley. I tried a few other small engines before remembering that Beautunaful Princess was a card and settled on the fish engine. It's actually pretty good, 1 card starter that gets you an omni-negate that pops with upside, and while it conflicts slightly it is really minor, and it was the perfect size, 3 consistency cards, 3 starters, and 1 brick. The brick is even not a brick sometimes.  The interruption suite has basically remained the same since inception, you need cards that don't conflict with Royal Tribute and are high impact.

deck_excerpt: A simple to use but effective deck for beginner and intermediate players.
deck_description:
Uhh so this deck is about synchro summoning using the effect of sword soul monster to summon token. You can also use tenyis instead of token for synchro but I prefer to use tenyis for support effect. This deck very solid and your main goal is to summon Cheng Ying, the Grand Swordsoul Duke and Chi Xiao, the Grand Swordsoul Swordmaster have a strong board (often deadly) - Here is a cool OTK combo to do if you have Tai A, the Swordsoul Swordmaster and Tenyi Spirit - Vishuda (and nothing on your board at that turn) + Activate the ability of Vishuda to sp-summon it (special summon). Link summon Monk using Vishuda as material. + Then normal summon Tai A then activate Tai A effect to summon a token by banishing Vishuda. Then synchro summon Chi Xiao. Then activate Chi Xiao when synchro summoned to add Long Yuan in to your hand (if you can/want to OTK) or add Sudden Shift as a control card (I gonna assume we added Long Yuan), also activate Tai A when send to GY (graveyard) effect to send Tenyi Spirit - Adhara to the GY + Banish Adhara from the GY to add back Vishuda from the banished zone. Then activate Long Yuan effect, tribute Vishuda to summon Long Yuan and also summon the token. Then synchro summon Cheng Ying, then activate Long Yuan effect in the GY to deal 1200 damage to your opponent.

 Now you have a Monk, Chi Xiao and Cheng Ying on the board which normally have a total damage of 6900 damage meanwhile your opponent has 6800. ALSO DONT FORGET that you also have a vishuda in the GY which you can banished it and remove 1 of your opponent card from the field, which also activate Cheng Ying effect to banish 2 more cards (1 from your opponent field, 1 from their GY), WHICHHHHH increase the damage of Cheng Ying by another 300.

You can go a step further if you can special summon 1 more monster (mostly by Ashuna or by Swordsoul Sacred Summit), you can link up to Shaman of the Tenyi using the Monk and the 1 normal monster you summoned, then activate Shaman, discard 1 card then bring back the Monk. Now your field end up with Cheng Ying, ChiXiao, Monk and Shaman

If you can go for both Cheng Ying , and Qixing thats a very very fun, OP combo. Banish, banish, destroy, destroy Pros:
  •  Easy to execute combos
  • Have pretty strong effect/removal
  • DESTRUCTIVE
Cons:
  • Get countered by Macro Cosmos/Mystic mine
  • Your combos can be ruined by card effect like Effect Veiler, Infinite Impermanence soo make sure you have a backup plan
  • Token collector (but for some reason I dont see much)
UPDATE: With the release of the new Swordsoul card: "Swordsoul Sinister Sovereign - Qixing Longyuan" which work pretty well with Cheng Ying so i added 2 into the deck, also changing up some synchros and tenyi link

deck_name: Just seeing the new D/D/D support
deck_description: I am horrible with D/D/D but I won’t lie, the new support looks good to me, really good.  It actually provides in archetype interruption which is very new to a deck like D/D/D, it allows you to lock yourself up now with the fiend locks and the like and still build a semi solid board.  The griffon is a neato card, it comes with a free extension, a trade in effect to flush out your hand, and a search if summoned from the graveyard, the problem is getting it to your graveyard but it can search any D/D card in general which is good considering the trap that’ll be reviewed later, all three of these effects suffer from hard opt but you can definitely trigger multiple effects in a turn.  Patented is kinda a funny card, I get the idea and it looks like it’ll work but I haven’t taken it for testing just yet, on the bright side it does recycle when it goes bye so spell and trap removal will trigger it and you’ll likely be able to get it out again via recycling.  D/D/D headhunt is actually really good, you can steal stuff and make them D/D/D monsters! In the zoodiac matchup if you trigger it on your turn and steal a big stack you can make a ridiculous makina  makina is a once per chain interruption which is really good because it can keep on stealing things again and again and it allows you to get its effect 3 straight times if you manage resolve thomas pop a pend zone to summon a ddd (most likely requium) overlay into dark Armageddon, take the popped card as overlay, recycle a graveyard contract if possible, then solo overlay into makina.

deck_excerpt: a pure goblin deck meant to teach beginners the basics of the game.
deck_description: a pure goblin deck meant to teach beginners the basics of the game.

"The Madolche Kingdom. A kingdom of sweets. An enigma to the people that visit this enchanted land. Ruled bya  monarch, the kingdom resembles a landscape made of various confections, with all the edibility that entails. The residents there are even strnagers, resembling plastic dolls or plush toys, thought inquiries into that are usually met with confusion. The two princesses are the talk of the kingdom. the heiress known as Puddingcess lives a charmed life as she attends her royal duties, prepares to inherit the throne, and tries to keep her little sister out trouble. Recent gossip claims that she is enamored with ser Chouxvalier, but he seems reluctant to confirm it. Among the nobility lie the royal staff, including the royal teacher Glassouffle, the clergywoman Sistart and the angel she is in communion with, Anjelly. Visitors are often left charmed by the kingdom's delights, thought her political neighbors often suspect something amiss, as if there is a fey air around it. Interestingly, a young child with an expansive doll collection went missing a year before contact with the kingdom as established, and no records tell of the kingdom's existence before that point, furthermore the missing child bore an uncanny resemblance to Queen Tiaramisu..." Well I haven't made a post in a while and I had some decks IRL to adapt to this site's decklist so I'd thought I'd rectify that for once. Be warned thought some aspects of this list are, puns aside, half-baked. The gameplan of the scrumptious Madolche kingdom seems to emphasize Summoning (mainly from the deck) and their adorable princesses, the eldest of which being needed for certain cards in the archetype to get bonus effects and herself has an Xyz variant that serves as a beater and another way to pull from the deck. The last common ingredient is a reliance on continuous backrow cards. They are predisposed for going second but have tools to weather the storm should they have to go first (of course some of those tools are out of theme and not ones I can apply to the deck yet). The main playmakers are Madolche Magileine, Madolche Petingcessoeur, Madolche Anjelly and Madolche Hootcake. Hooty and Angelly here both summon direclty from the deck, as does Petingcessoeur, but in her case that is meant to bring out her big sister, Madolche Puddingcess as the kid reduces the level of any monster she summons and otherwise messes up the Rank 4 plays with any other monster. Magileine OTOH is just a searcher, but one with no HOPT. Another important card is Madolche Messingelato who can fetch a needed spell card if he's special summoned. Madolche Mewfeuille is another normal summon that can summon out another Madolche from your hand. Madolche Cruffsant meanwhile is card that bounces a Madolche to grant himself a level and 300 ATK, a little niche TBF but it is another way for Rank 4 plays and helping proc certain cards. Moving onto the spells we have Madolche Chateau, Madolche Salon and Madolche Ticket, all of which are important to the strategy and play off of each other in interesting ways. Chateau is a field spell that brings every doll in the GY back to the deck to ensure certain effects are live and if any subsequent monsters left there are returned to the deck you have the option of bringing them to the hand instead (and it has a 500 ATK boost to Madolche monsters). This brings us to Ticket which can special summon or search monsters every time Madolche cards are returned to the hand or main deck. Last but not least is Salon, which gives us an extra normal summon (Notable because the archetype does have a few cards that plus on normal summon, two of whcih were already mentioned and of those two at least one isn't HOPT) and also helps to search backrow   Moving onto the traps. Madolche Lesson is a simple 800 ATK boost, decent by the standards of such powerups but the effect itself is mediocre since the focus is away from the battle phase. still it can help close out games considering that Puddingcess's Xyz version can reach 3800 with this and Chateau active. Madolche Nights serves as a monster negate and with Puddingcess herself out a way to remove a card by returning it to the deck. Madolchepalooza is...mostly there for fun, the effect to summon any amount of in theme monsters form your hand is nice but kinda wasteful economy wise given they will all return to the deck at the end and as a trap you can't use thus turn one. Madolche Promenade is the deck's best trap yet, negating a monster in exchange for bouncing one of your own, while also have an effect that lets you attach a Madolche monster to one of their xyz. Onto the Extra deck, the off-theme ones were cobbled together from cards I have that weren't in another deck. ranging from the metaish such as Borreload Dragon and Mekk-Knight Crisadia Avramax  to some small utility like Knightmare Phoenix and Barricadeborg Blocker, to the less played such as Evigishki Merrowgeist and Topologic Trisbaena. Of course the majority of the ED is dedicated to copies of the 4 in theme monsters. Staring with the OG boss monster, Madolche Queen Tiaramisu. Tiaramisu is a primarily reason why the deck wants to go second as her effect a powerful piece of removal with a rate quality that moots certain forms of responses and "cannot be targeted" effects. For going first we have Madolche Fresh Sistart and Madolche Teacher Glassouffle, which serve to protect your backrow and one of your monsters, respectably. the latter also has a nifty recycling effect that procs when another Madolche goes to the GY, helping to keep your GY clean. The last monster is Madolche Puddingcess Chocolat-a-la-mode. Puddingcess here taking on a new dress, 1500 extra ATK and the ability to summon a mosnter from the dekc (provided Puddingcess herself is an overlay unit, this explains Petingcesouer and Prominade's effects) Madolche Butlerusk is another monster that search a card on Normal summon, however instead of a Madolche cards it is instead a field spell. the catch is that you need another Madolche monster to use it, if you're wondering why this dude wasn't teched in every deck that uses a field spell. He's here more becuase of the fact that I don't currently run Terraforming and Metaverse (despite having a lot of copies of them, I am considering them of course) Madolche Tea Break is a counterpart to Nights, whereas Nights responds to Monster effects, this card responds to spells, and like Nights,m it also has a Puddingcess reliant bonus effect. In this case popping a card. Madolche Waltz is in the side deck concept for some cute Game 3 memes, as it is a burn card that deals 300 damage each time one of your dolls battle, it can also potentially close out games (Puddingcess Chocolat with 3800 ATK plus this means up to 4100 damage), but the changes are minor. Last card of note is Trap Trick. This one helps search your Normal Traps provided you can spare a copy of the one you want to search and lets you activate it the same turn. Naturally if I do have these in the IRL deck the ratios of some of the traps would bump up. thus ends my Madolche deck profile. I am aware that this is half baked and that other options are available (Traptrix Raflessia+Gravedigger's for starters). It is for that reason that I will appreciate any feed back you have on this deck. Especially where the Extra is concerned.

deck_description: Metalfoes deck using Magical Abductor and Sky Striker engine instead of Rescue Rabbit.  GLHF

Main goal is to go into First Darklord via Theatre and protect the castle. First turn setups are less about putting several negates/floodgates up and moreso about establishing a variety of different disruption, protection, and floating effects via backrow, monster effects, and GY setup, then pushing through whatever your opponent throws at you while accruing card advantage. OTKs come easy thanks to huge stat totals as well as Quaeritis's ATK zeroing and easy access to the Numeron Dragon package. Guardian Chimera fits perfectly into the deck, providing strong removal and cycling on a big body while triggering Despia on-Fusion effects, making it pretty much your best choice when using Branded in Red. In conlusion, Konami, please don't ban/limit Aluber just because you decided to print a bunch of broken Branded/Albaz support that doesn't do anything for this deck.

deck_excerpt: My ideal body type is water.
deck_description:
Oh boy, another Marincess decklist It's been quite a while since the last one and don't worry, I don't plan to write this one exclusively in Nickelback song titles.   New Fish in the Ocean Marincess was never a bad archetype to begin with. That was in large parts thanks to their Cyberse typing which in and of itself boosts the powerlevel of any of its given archetypes. Still, it felt like these fish were floating around the East Blue rather than the Grand Line if you know what I mean. They could pack a punch, take a bite but all in all weren't all that frightening. But guess what, we're swimming with the big boys now. There's plenty of fish in the Ocean and the Ocean just, got, bigger. Let's talk support. The Goodies:
  • Marincess Springirl: Or Spring Girl? Either way this card's great. It's a level 4 extender with a trigger effect if sent to the GY, allowing for more *in deep, echo-y voice* CHAINBLOCKING. It can mill cards from the top of the deck equal to the number of Marincess monsters you control. Lemme translate. "Here's another shot at Wave". So many cards can recycle from the GY, this is an add effect with an attitude.....or additude SORRY
  • Marincess Sleepy Maiden: What's this? Another extender? Konami is going wild today. It's biggest weakness is its level. It's a *gags* Level 5 *shudders*. It's a pretty free extender, requiring no banishing or a set amount of Marincess monsters on the field. Any Marincess equals 2 Marincesses with this tired gal. The problem is that the Marincess Link-1s need a Level 4 or lower Marincess monster, don't ask why.
  • Marincess Dive: And for the third card I present you: An..extender? Did Konami really just print three in-archetype extenders? Who of you madmen sold their soul to Konami again, huh? Leaving aside the large amount of firstbornes Konami is bound to receive in about 2-3 business days, this card is actually pretty bonkers. It's a Special Summon from the GY for your non-Link Marincess monsters or, if you already control Battle Ocean it straight up Special Summons from deck. That means that drawing Battle Ocean doesn't actually make you brick since you can then add this to hand instead using Sea Angel. This card also allows any Level 4 or lower Marincess Monster to enable a Link-4. Without the Field Spell but if you're loaded with handtraps and a Wave, who cares?
  • Marincess Aqua Argonaut: I don't know if here name is derived from a certain useless goddess of if she used to accompany Jason on their search for their golden Feeces. Fleeces. I mean Fleece. Something golden that's not poop. Anyways she's the newest Link-4 and despite her name is pretty dang useful. She Special Summons one of her equiped Marincess Links in order to negate a Spell/Trap card or effect. Pretty cool. The worst part about her is that you now need too decide between her negate and Bubble Reef's draw. If that seems too hard just go with your heart, your gut or whatever is found beneath, whichever one helps.
The Oopsie Daisies:
  • Marincess Bubble Ring: This card is a situational attack negate and I think that's all that needs to be said. Very slow, very weak, someone was hesitant to give up their firstborne and this is our punishment. Thanks..
  • Marincess Circulation: This trap is kinda like Snow. You swap one WATER Link for a Marincess Link with the same rating. Super duper situational. While it's cool to think that you could use Aqua's S/T negate or draw a card with Bubble Reef and then tag them out for the other I'd really prefer any other card in my deck over this one.
  What's remained Let me start by saying no two Marincess decklists are the same. They tend to be very different from one another. Some might play way more extenders, some may still be on the Frogs. For this one I took my old version and updated it accordingly. I'd consider my decklist to be quite teched while some prefer it simple. However I like the tech choices and I think they're strong. I'm not gonna go over my Dinomiscus or Fury-Torrential ratios, I've done that in the past already. It's the same idea of running a good amount of handtraps, some backrow to protect your tower for a strong turn 1 that exceeds the standalone Marincess combo line to then finish off your opponent with an unfair amount of ressources on the following turn.   What's changed For starters, I added the new stuff but I think you figured. Sleepy Maiden is a one off for me since it doesn't equal full combo, is "just" an extender and this deck plays plenty. It's nice to have tho. Springirl is another three off since it's Level 4. I upped Pascalus up to two copies, although even three would be viable now. There are way more targets and she tooo can climb into a Link-4 now. Also, her recursion matters more as there are more good S/Ts which can be recursed. Dive's a three off for me since it's just really powerful. I added Sea Nettle since there's plenty of WATER boss monsters now to OTK and turn 1 it's just the best Level 4 extender. I got rid of the frogs. What I didn't like about them is how win more Swap Frog felt. You needed a really good hand if you wanted to summon Toadally Awesome within 5 summons. And summoning Toadally after your combo felt very win more since at that point any form of extra interaction is great. Swap is very heavy on the ressources and with the new Level 4 Marincess and the Spell which can also be used to summon a Level 4 I found that this decklist can summon Toadally way more consistently that the previous one, which relied on pretty much exactly Swap and a good hand. Of course I've previously neverleaned hard into the Level 4 extenders but now I feel quite confident in cutting the Swaps without lowering this decks ceiling.   Access who? I admit, I'm still on the Talkers. But great news, this deck is now completely viable without spending 200 bucks on four arrows. There are so many extenders now in this deck that it's no longer reliant on Accesscode to close out games. Don't get me wrong, Marincess still lack a way to out monsters without attacking into them but you can extend into way more bodies now and since you'll have so much ED space you can run a larger r4nk engine with cards like Abyss Dweller or Number 4: Stealth Kragen with two Kragen Spawn. The Kragens also count as a means to remove monster during the MP, making OTKing without Access all the easier.
Ghostrick

It's got a few interesting tech choices in such as King of Feral Imps, and Machine Duplication.  Not meant to be competitive, but one could easily cut one of each four star Springan, and some of the traps to add hand traps.  Opted to throw an experimental brew in the sideboard. deck_excerpt: My favorite deck version while we don't know BODE support spoliers
deck_description: This is the version I've been testing in this format and I'm enjoying it the most. Hope it brings you new ideas, this is the most fun deck I've been playing since launch. I like the card ratios but I'll show you the differences you'll find in other builds: 3 Sting Lancer and 3 Scout Buggy = many builds only use two of each. I like to maximize the Beetrooper monsters because they are the best cards in the deck along with the Resonance Insect and they always give you an advantage so I want to see them in my starting hand, not to mention that in more grind matches their third copy shows up a lot. Kaiju is the card that I feel the most that cutting from the main deck is good because there are a lot of hands that I brick with it. I think Parasite Paranoid is a card that plays the same role as Contact "C" in most cases that are in matches against Salamangreat and Ignister that have Link 1 that need Cyberse monsters to be summoned and especially against the Tri-Brigade it's practically another copy of Contact "C" that you lock a Link monster from it after the first effect you lock on Beast-Type resolves. Another deck that I've taken a lot of value from is against ABC when he activates Union Hangar to equip from the deck. The only matches that only Contact "C" works are on decks focused on the Archetype name like Zoodiac and Prank-kids so I use a copy in the side deck. Parasite Paranoid also shines in random situations like for example the opponent activates a monster effect that targets an Insect you control like Double Dragon Lords (if it doesn't send it as a cost to the GY) or ABC Buster Dragon among others functioning as a protection to your move. Another interesting situation is it protects your monster from being destroyed by battle, for example you pass Seraphim Papillon with 2 counters verses Eldlich and you prevent the Golden Lord from attacking you and Papillon is guaranteed to use the effect twice and stay alive for the turn. The third important situation of Parasite Paranoid is you equip it on any monster on the field that will be sent to the GY either to Link Climb or destroyed by battle or card effect and then use its second effect to summon usually from the Doom Dozer ignoring the summoning Condition which has been helpful to me 2 times. The last engine thing I did was take out the Battlewasp Twinbow and use Butterfly instead because that way the Underworld Goddess is much easier to happen because I easily put 3 effect monsters on the field and use Opponent's Apollousa or I:P Masquerena as material which I really like this option because Apollousa is a big problem for this deck since most of the monsters you summon have very low atk and Butterfly have 1200atk who can already get the Wind Barrier Statue or a Herald of the Arc Light. His being Wind also improves the situation of you being on Gozen Match because it's much better for you to try to play with the Wind monsters as you play Cicada King, Shinobi and Papillon and try to survive until you get an out. Not to mention that it makes a difference if you have more Bugs in GY and Butterfly is perfect to be banned at any time. If you draw multiples you simply discard the second with Picophalena's effect. The extra deck of the nine Insect cards that I highly recommend using because it always has utility, Shinobi is the only one that I never use its effect but to my surprise its continuous effect cannot be targeted by attacks has saved me a few times in grind game with simplified gamestate. As for the generic monsters I highly recommend you use Almiraj because it makes the Resonance Insect a live card at the same time you have enough game volume to leave it on the field and use only one zone to play and thus protect yourself from cards like Chuche, Punishment and Torrential Tribute taking the opponent by surprise. Phoenix and Trisbaena are other excellent cards in this deck and indispensable, Trisbaena you have several ways to trigger its effect, the main one is the Beetrooper Formation, but you also have Sting Lancer, Doom Dozer and this guarantees you to win backrow which is the main deficiency of this deck. Otherwise the other Extra Deck cards can be any other utility card like Knightmare Cerberus or Unicorn, Unchained Abomination etc. The choices of tech cards in the main deck as well as the side deck are just options that I present, you can assemble it according to the meta. Just be smart with Nibiru because sometimes you lock Bugs and you can't use it but it's a price to pay to survive and take the turn back. What I expect from the new support are more Advantage Enabler or monsters with Floating effects and especially a Link 3 or Link 5 with interaction effect even if it's a Pop every turn like the Phoenix Enforcer does. I expect a link that gives properties to the Invincible Atlas like for example: Insect monster that was made using this card as material gains this effect: Once per turn, if an Insect is summoned in a zone that this card points to: send a card that your opponent controls for the gy. I think it's perfect because this deck summons on the opponent's turn and Atlas is currently a very weak win condition, it's not just because it has dragoon protection that it's competent. I would also like a link 2 that does Picofalena's work, but it doesn't need to discard cards and equip a Banned Insect on it to keep looping the resonance insect in the grind game, because locking on insects is more interfering than helping because there's not much where go since the Insect type has very weak extra deck cards that don't help you put pressure on the field. But the big problem with this deck is that you need to use a lot of bad extender to make combo so this deck deserves to extend like Dragon Link which gives you an advantage as Noctovision makes Chain Block and draws cards and also an efficient way to deal with spells/traps which is horrible these days.

deck_excerpt: A Fluffal deck profile featuring Guardian Chimera!
deck_description: OK, so when Guardian Chimera was shown to be a real card, I was blown away. The artwork was amazing, the effects were strong yet balanced, and the summoning condition made sure it wasn't overpowered. I chose to put this in a Fluffals deck for two reasons.  One, Fluffals are good at getting a bunch of monsters in their hand, and two, Guardian Chimera is a go-second card, while Fluffals are a go-second deck. And due to the obvious killer doll theme, I decided to name this profile "Deck of Chucky." Which is ironic, considering that I saw a Chucky movie on TV last week.     Anyways, this deck is NOT meant to go first. Your only first turn play is summoning Frightfur Sheep, or getting Edge Imp Scythe and getting a Fluffal monster--ideally Fluffal Penguin--into your hand. You want to go second, especially since some of the monsters in this deck WANT to be sent to the Graveyard. Edge Imp Chain, Fluffal Cat, et cetera.

deck_excerpt: Danger Gren Maju. OTK. Current/post BODE meta.
deck_description: Welcome back to to yet another updated Gren Maju build. With the way the current and likely meta is going to shape once BODE becomes TCG legal, I felt the need to shift from a handtrap Golden Castle based build to a more grindy and even more LVL 8 oriented build. Crossout Designator made handtraps even less effective as well all know. Also with the current meta running more Veiler and Imperms, the OTK that would often be provided by Dragubilon and Numeron Dragon is a lot harder to achieve, and Golden Castle simply burns too much through a 40 card build to risk using anymore.  The deck has seen a marked increase in LV:8's with the additions of Gadarla (vital for Barrier Statue spammers), Gamecial and Alpha. Kaiju's are often my go to to get rid of annoyingly tough to remove omni-negates and other interruptions (Dragoon/Enforcer/Baroness/Ultimatness.. you get the idea). Looping Alpha with Kaiju's is often a good way to eat through several layers of interruption and Alpha being a 3k beatstick allows it to clean up most of what is left. With this increase in LV:8's brings additional drawing power in the form of Trade-In, being useful not only to draw additional cards, but also activate the Danger monster effects should the need arise. Interrupted Kaiju Slumber provides both removal as well as ensuring I can get to a vital Kaiju to further prevent the opponent being able to regain a board. Gizmek/Eater Of Millions and Pot Of Desires as we all know do the job of deck thinning and banishing to allow Gren Maju to swing. Additional facedown removal from Eater is also at times of great benefit. Eater has been moved up from 1 in my Golden Castle builds to 2, to have a more balanced method of winning. Lightning Storm, Harpie's and Pankratops provide excellent removal as well.  Not much really needs to be said about the side deck. I'm pretty much happy with it as is. Dingirsu/Zeus are as strong as they've always been with non-targeting and non-destructive removal. Sanaphond has really come into it's own, as shutting off graveyard revival prevents Enforcer from coming back via it's own effect, as well as shutting down a great deal of the meta's ability to rebuild boards from the grave. Lancelot is surprisingly good with it's ability to poke directly for 2k damage. With life points likely to be low on the opponents end most of the time, this can often be critical. The added negating of any type of activation is a little bonus as well. N'tss to punish Dogmatika. Knightmare's Phoenix, Unicorn and BLS can come up from time to time, but Zeroboros/Accesscode are mainly there as additional win cons and to be honest lack of any real alternatives that fit with the deck. Out of everything in the Extra, these two I can't say have ever come up, nor have there been situations where they could've helped. But you never know, may find some uses at some point.  Dimension Shifter is sat in the side deck. Although still immensely strong and crippling to the vast majority of decks, without knowing the impact of Flunder's on the meta, I would rather have a reasonably solid 40 card main deck that is decently effective against everything (of course the die roll greatly skews this) rather than have a few cards that are utterly useless Game 1 when dealing with what could be frequent matchup. Ra Sphere is 3 Kaiju's in one, and is one of the few cards capable of flat out cleaning Drytron and the monster portion of Phantom Knight boards, which could otherwise prove tricky, if not impossible to get around. Can also come in handy against Swordsoul, as they can have three monsters on board as well. Being a normal summon is also helpful should I walk into Barrier Statue +2 monster boards, and doesn't usually interfere with the deck's strategy, as everything bar Gren Maju is a special summon anyway. Double Twins and Red Reboot are additional backrow coverage, whilst DD Ground, Summon Limit and Imperial Order all provide the ability to completely stun all the match ups i'm likely to face.     As always, feel free to like and comment!

https://youtu.be/laHDaJCYLn8

Necro-Pendulum? It does mean giving up Scythe, and it conflicts a little with Tuning Magician and Selene, but on the other hand if your game is Necro-Goon, Necro Apollousa-Bagooska-Dragoon seems like upside. Of course, the downside is you're pendulum, there isn't a lot of space for hand traps or other interaction before you settle on Necrovalley, and none afterwards.  So, we've got 2 separate pendulum engines in the deck, a large Pendulum Magicians Engine, and a smaller Darkwurm engine. For Magicians I'm on 3 Wisdom Eye, the best Pendulum Magician and a card you want to open, 3 Oafdragon Magician, our main low scale and a way to recur monsters from the extra deck, 3 Double Iris, because sometimes you'll want to pop this to get an extra interaction, 1 Tuning Magician for combos with Halq and Selene, 3 Harmonizing Magician, the second-best magician in the deck, an instant Needlefibre off of its pendulum summon, 2 Skullcrobat Joker which is just fine, it is technically a consistency card, then 1 of the Time Pendulumgraph for the extra interruption, 1 Star Pendulumgraph, technically a consistency card, also technically searchable protection, 3 Pendulum Call to pitch Darkwurm and search us our pen magicians, and lastly 3 Duelist Alliance to search Pen Call and Double Iris.  For the Darkwurm engine, we're on all 3 Darkwurm and all 3 Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon to search Darkwurm, and the Supreme King Gate Zero, a necessary brick for Darkwurm. I felt like consistency was key in pendulums and like Pen Call pitch Darkwurm was a combo I wanted to see often enough, this is just guaranteed scales and easy access to a strong combo where both pieces are searchable.  For our last package, we're running Dragoon. Look, I just... okay? The deck is great at making Apollousa + Bagooska but Apollo + Dragoon is probably more appealing to end on in a lot of circumstances, and when it pushes to Dragoon + Apollo + Bagooska + Necrovalley that seems pretty scary to confront. Note that the Rank 4 can be easy access to a 4-5 material Zeus through Utopia, and that Apollo can often be Unicorn-Accesscode, so the deck has the tools to break boards with that package.  7 copies of Necrovalley. While it does make some sense to run more, I think you do flood out with excess copies more often when you do that, and the space in this deck is real tight, especially with Dragoon, and your odds of seeing a copy at 7 are high enough that it'll probably be there in at least 1 of your games if it is actually good. The reason we run 1 of the spell and 2 of the Commandant is that the first copy of the spell is better for Selene's purposes, but being once per turn makes the second copy worse.  So, just gonna run through the deck real fast. 1 Halq, just an easy to summon extender that enables combos. 2 Selene, because of Necrovalley you aren't using the second copy as often but you still want it for follow-ups when you didn't draw Necrovalley. 1 Apollo, your big boss monster, typically ends on 2 negates, but with Bagooska back-up it can actually get them. 1 Unicorn, and 1 Accesscode are a nice little package of board breaking cards that can also deal with set backrow. Dragoon also helps break boards, but is an omni-negate and also has very good protection that make it annoying. Tornado Dragon is here to pop our own Double Iris and that's about it, but it can also help take down backrow. Bagooska is here to protect Apollo, since we're summoning it at few negates. Abyss Dweller is here in case we pop off without Necrovalley. The last cards in the extra deck are Utopia into Zeus, with 4 or maybe even 5 materials.

deck_excerpt: Set opponent's attack to 0 & chip away boards
deck_description: Deck is made for trad format, side deck has meta relevant cards/handtraps that can help the deck out. If swapping to make a legal deck that uses handtraps, swap PoG, surface, & the 2 water hazards.  Main goal of the deck is to slam down Cosmocroix early to lock up opponent's monster effects. Agel can draw either Cradel card, depending on what you need, but if you have Cosmocroix or Icejade Cradel in hand, add the field, if you have Inion Cradel or Terraforming in hand, add Icejade Cradel instead.  Sea serpent cards in the deck are the basis for all the synchro monsters, with Diva being able to pull one of 2 ways to synchro to 7 or going into Halq to which pulls another tuner (usually Minstrel) and any one of 4 tuner synchros. Clear Wing helps protect Cosmocroix, Dragite negates backrow, Brionac is used to setup Moulinglacia as it allows you to choose how many water monsters go in your grave & provides minimum 1 target for Moulinglacia to discard.  XYZ's are much more difficult to get out as most require Acty to summon as it's the only level 4 in the Main Deck. Should you be able to summon them, Number 37  can work in tandem with Cosmocroix to make your opponents lose 4600 attack for 2 turns. Silent Honor ARK helps remove big Extra Deck monsters while bypassing destruction protections, Bahamut Shark & Toadally Awesome combo sets up a spell/trap negation, Leviair helps pull back icejades that have banished themselves and allows for some recursion in the deck, and Abyss Dweller is mainly for if you no longer have Cosmocroix & your opponent is trying to use grave shenanigans.  Called by  & minstrel provide protection against Ash Blossom which is one of the worst handtraps for this deck as you need to pull a cards from deck w/ agel unless you  open with a perfect hand. Side deck provides additional protections in the way of instant fusion/restrict or dragged down/dimension shifter. Infinite impermanence is among the best cards in the side deck to switch out for as it stacks w/ Cosmocroix to prevent monster effects even on the turn they're summoned, letting you stun your opponent. Nibiru & DPE packages are both for removing big threats, Nibiru keeps things from ever hitting the board, while DPE stops effects that don't proc on summon & has flexibility to destroy back row as well.
