deck_excerpt: A guide on one of Trinity Format's best control decks
deck_description:
Why play plants?

Pros: Extremely versatile answers, Generates massive amounts of card advantage, Great stalling potential, Access to multiple "Dridents", Powerful game ending disruption cards, Strong Mid-Late Game. Cons: Difficult to pilot effectively, Weak to disruption, Sometimes bricky, Difficult to close games out with, Slow early game, long games (if you don't like that sort of thing)

Card/Engine Choices

Rikka: Your main advantage engine comes from Rikka Petal, when activated it searches you any "Rikka" monster and during our opponent's End Phase it summons itself back. Our choice of main deck monsters are Snowdrop the Rikka Fairy which is our XYZ/Synchro enabler, Mudan the Rikka Fairy who searches Rikka Sheet to disrupt our opponents or Rikka Tranquility that lets us stall or setup and Extra Deck play, Primula the Rikka Fairy who is a free body and helps us make our Rank 4 and 6 and lastly Erica the Rikka Fairy who lets us beat over big boss monsters and can revive itself from grave. Next is the Extra Deck Rikka's, First is Rikka Queen Strenna which is how we recycle our Rikka S/T and when tributed can "rank-up" into the other 2 if needed, Then we have Kanzashi the Rikka Queen that protects our monsters by tributing a plant monster in hand or field if they would be destroyed and can also act as Monster Reborn when a card has been tributed, Lastly is Teardrop the Rikka Queen who is our main boss monster and 1 of our main disruption tools, her first effect lets us Tribute our opponents monsters at SS2 and the second effect booster her by 200atk every time a card(s) is tributed. Aroma: This is our second advantage engine which has high synergy with Rikka and gives us access to strong cards like Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram, Aromage Marjoram, Aromaseraphy Jasmine and Blessed Winds. Sweet Marjoram does it all, SS2 Pop, Targeting protection and searches one of our key cards Blessed Winds which in tandem with her creates an infinite value engine that can either recycle our other engines, let us dodge banishing removal, Trigger sent to GY effs or revive something every turn all while keeping our lifepoints topped up. Aromage Marjoram is our GY Disruption and Battle Phase punisher while Aromaseraphy Jasmine is battle protection that synergises well with petal to tutor any plant we want out of our deck. These two engines together create an extremely potent control shell that is flexible and gives us a ridiculous amount of card advantage. Predaplant: This give us more disruption with predaplanning, strong fusion boss monsters and access to Super Polymerization one of the strongest board breaking cards in the game. This engine really helps solidify our mid game and keep our opponent off of big boss monsters. Traps: Our trap line-up is simple, Disrupt as much as possible. The rest are pure advantage cards that further push our greedy mid-late game.    

Openers

  Our deck isn't that dependent on getting a starter but knowing what your options are is important here's the most common openers for the deck. Petal into Mardel: Summon Rikka Petal and activate its effect to search Mudan the Rikka Fairy, summon Mudan by tributing Petal and Activate Mudan to search Either Rikka Sheet for disruption or Rikka Tranquility for value. This is our standard opener and what we will typically do against most decks. 1 Card Marjoram Setups: Normal summon Mathematician, sending Dandylion and summon 2 Tokens, Link Mathematician and 1 of the tokens into Crossrose Dragon and activate its effect sending it and the other token to the GY, summon Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram and activate her effect to search Blessed Winds. This opener is really great against rogue or unrefined strategies since a single disruption is enough to derail these kind of decks but can punished by certain decks. Jasmine/Mardel: Summon Mathematician in the Centre Column and send Dandylion to summon 2 Tokens, Link the 2 Tokens into Aromaseraphy Jasmine and activate its effect tributing Mathematician to summon Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light and search either Petal to get the Rikka engine started or Rose Girl if your engine is already going. This opener is really only ideal into control matchups since it gives us our engine as quickly as possible while also providing solid defense. Set 4 Pass: This is probably the 2nd most common opener in this deck but not necessarily a brick, as long as we can continually disrupt the opponent they will eventually have the same ceiling for power that we currently do, which is exactly what we want because we have inevitability in that once we draw our engine cards we can easily start out advantaging our opponent and win from there.

Midgame

  Midgame is tricky because its extremely dependent on what your opponent is doing and what you have access to but generally at this point you should be deciding how many turns you can realistically close the game out in and how you are going to accomplish it. Here are some things to look out for in the midgame. Abusing Blessed Winds: Blessed Winds is one of your key cards in the mid game using each effect to its fullest potential is important. Keeping your engine's going with the first of effect is crucial to get into a winning position, shuffling back your Rikka cards ensures you have the fuel to keep grinding out your opponent. Dodging removal with the 2nd effect is probably the single most important thing to keep in mind at all times, remember we only have 1 Rikka Petal and no way to recover it, if it's banished we are suddenly cut off from one of our main engines. The 3rd effect is basically just looping both marjoram's if they hit grave, it doesn't come up that often but can be strong when you get the chance. Predaplant's: Midgame is where predaplants start becoming more relevant, Predaplanning can keep our opponent off of XYZ's and Synchro's while Predaplant Sarraceniant and Predaplant Drosophyllum Hydra can act as unconventional removal. Predaplant Verte Anaconda also spikes in the midgame turning any 2 monsters into Super Polymerization which can be game winning on it's own. Establishing Bosses: In the midgame we really want to summon our boss monsters like Teardrop the Rikka Queen and Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram and keep reviving them with cards like Rikka Tranquility, Blessed Winds and Super Team Buddy Force Unite!, this often ends up being your win condition. The Advantage Trinity: This is the point in the game where your secondary advantage engines start kicking in, Card of Safe Return, Dark Factory Of More Production and Supply Squad, These cards give us immense card draw and let us draw into our powerful trap cards in order to keep disrupting our opponent. Making the most of our traps: Traps are our main way of controlling the pace of the game and defending ourselves from big pushes from the opponent, knowing when and how to use your traps is matchup dependent but there are some fundamental's you can apply to any matchup.
  • Always keep your opponent's summon limit in mind when choosing when to use your disruption.
  • Is the card worth removing? If the card is easily removed in battle refrain from using your removal too early and save it for a bigger threat.
  • Am I on a clock? A clock refers to the amount of turns your opponent can lethal you from, if you feel like your opponent is trying to race you down then you can be more loose with your removal cards.
  • How much has my opponent committed to a play? The more value you can get from each of your removal cards the better, shotguning your Ring of Destruction too early might leave you with less value than if you had waited.
 

Late Game

  Ending the game: By this point we should have enough board presence to close the game out with our boss monsters, always keep cards like Super Team Buddy Force Unite! and Erica the Rikka Fairy in mind when trying to close out games. Don't get too greedy: Ensure your plays are all trying to close out the game, don't keep playing for value as you may get punished by a top-deck from your opponent.

deck_excerpt: Necrovalley in Altergeists? Somebody stop me! (This is only maybe good, and won't be for long, but it is a good reference for what the package could l
deck_description: So let me preface this deck by saying this - unless you think Necrovalley is actually very good when you play it, don't play it in Altergeists. This is kind of a test list, just me drumming up another deck that can make use of Necrovalley while it is good. Having said that, I'm not sure it is good enough to run in this meta, and Altergeists isn't a perfect home for it. It certainly won't be good enough post-BODE. Still, I thought the idea was intriguing, so I decided to share my list.  The next thing I want to say is that I am not an expert at Altergeists. I still don't even know their combos, and the deck for some reason has always been hard for me to get a grasp on. I think I'm finally starting to figure out why Altergeists are so powerful however, this deck excels at putting up interaction, for a dumb trap deck the engine is really quite good. Slow the game down to where 1 for 1 trades matter and win on high quality 1 for 1 trades.  I went for a version with no hand traps, aside from Imperm which makes the cut for being a trap card for Multifaker. There are a couple of reasons for this. Firstly, there just wasn't space to fit in a Necrovalley package with 6 hand traps. Secondly, hand traps other than Imperm, obviously, are too low-impact this format to be worth running when instead to can run plans that are still good going second.  So, onto the line-up. Pretty standard for Altergeist cards, 3 Meluseek, 3 Multifaker, 3 Mario, 1 Kunquery, 2 Silq, with 3 Spoofing, 2 Protocol, and 1 Manifestation. The standard line-up is fine in Necrovalley, some effects get shut off but Protocol protects most of your effects. 3 Meluseek, 3 Multifaker, and 3 Spoofing is for easy access to multifaker. 3 Mario 2 Protocol is still correct, since you need your number of Altergeist monsters to be higher and since Protocol is better as a card searched by Mario than drawn on its own. 1 Manifestation, the first effect still works under Protocol which is when you will search for this, and you won't always draw Necrovalley, which will likely hurt the opponent more. Still a 1 of, just here to search.  Then we have exactly 5 copies of Necrovalley, the 3 actual copies plus 1 Terraforming and 1 Metaverse. Metaverse is necessary for increasing the number of traps cards in the deck, and is just better than Commandant here (and maybe elsewhere). It lets you back up a Necrovalley with another instant-speed copy if you see them together. We run exactly 5 of these cards, because while you do want to see a copy you never really want to see multiple copies of this card, and because this way you have the perfect sized package to side in Secret Village of the Spellcasters and Imperial Order (side out Terraforming).  Pot of Extra is here to dig through cards, and from here on out everything is pretty standard. Imperms for the Multifaker interaction, Solemns, and a few tech-choice traps. I really like Torrential Tribute combined with Solemn Strike in this deck as a board breaking tool, so I'm on 3 Torrential Tribute. I'm also on Dogmatika Punishment, because the downside doesn't matter and getting to pop 2 is huge upside.  So, one downside with the deck is you're playing with Necrovalley in 1/3 of your games. The Secret Village plan is too important to run Necrovalley most of the time in games 2 and 3, realistically. So you're looking to cheese game 1s with Necrovalley and then play future games with Secret Village. Is that really worth the space? You have to ask yourself that. But remember 1 game is half of what you need to win a match, so the answer to this could be yes, if Necrovalley will cheese you those game 1s in your meta. The other downside is you are hurting yourself in some ways that are crucial to your own grind game - in a grindy enough format this might not be the answer, and it's one of the reasons that even though Necrovalley stacks up well against the top decks right at this moment, I don't know if it is good enough to run in Altergeists right now. However, this version is overall, quite functional, and has the potential to grind those games out under Necrovalley, so don't be discouraged to try it if you're expecting a lot of Dry and Tri in your meta.  Overall I'm glad I made this deck list. It helped me learn a little about Altergeists, and I feel like I have a better understanding of the deck now than before I built this list.

deck_excerpt: A deck using the Speedroid archetype
deck_description: This was one of my favorite decks to make, all because of  the fact that when I started playing Yugioh, I had a deck with just a small amount of different archetypes because I only bought booster packs. And within that deck, the Speedroid cards I had were my go-to cards to help me win in the end. And so, I decided to finally get around to making this deck. There's only two ways I can see this deck going wrong. 1, You don't get any tuners in your starting hand (which shouldn't be very likely), and 2, Having your opponent OTK you. I'm mostly worried about being OTKed, mainly because of the fact that a decent amount of the Speedroid's effects revolve around summoning from the graveyard, but that's only some of them. Anyway, onto the strategy I planned. STEP ONE - The first thing you need to do is get out a decent Synchro monster so you at least have a little bit of protection. I recommend Chanbara, to help get it's ATK boosted before your opponent can get some high-levels on the field. STEP TWO - Next, you need to get out Kitedrake, but ONLY ONE!!! You need to keep the other one in the Extra Deck, so you have some board wipe abilities for late game. STEP THREE - Finally, you need to get out your Clear Wings to help you keep up some high ATK. With this, you should be secured the win. I took a lot of pride making this deck, and I think it'll work very well. Best of luck on your next duel!

deck_excerpt: Eldlich with a small Zombie package
deck_description: The Eldlich cards are Zombie support, right? I mean, look, they say Zombie right on the card? Well, not quite. I've struggled when building Zombie Eldlich decks in the past. The Eldlich engine is a testy thing that takes tuning to hum, and previous builds have felt schizophrenic. When I sit down to pilot a deck I want to know what deck I am piloting, not some hybrid deck where half the time I'm playing Eldlich and half the time I'm playing Zombies. So the marriage of the two archetypes was not as natural as you might have suspected.  However, Golden Lord is straight up a Zombies card, Zombie World doesn't conflict with Eldlich cards gameplan and is good right now, and by running a small zombies package and a more formidable Eldlich Line I know what the deck is - an Eldlich deck that runs Zombie World and very occasionally Balerdroch.  So, starting from the top, I put in my tech cards first. 3 Zombie World, as a floodgate that disrupts a lot of different archetypes, 1 Necroworld Banshee as copy #4, plus 1 Foolish Burial as copy 5 of Zombie World as well as being a way to send Bloom or even just Golden Lord. Then Solemns and Imperm, because these cards are good, at this point these are pretty obligatory in my Eldlich builds for their power and versatility. For Golden Land trap monsters, 3 Conquistador, and 2 Huaqero is probably the best ratio. You don't need to grind forever, and 5 of these are the right number, since you only need to access 1 Eldlixer in most turns, and since you need to summon Golden Lord for them to be live you don't want to brick on these cards. 1 Golden Land Forever, because it is a searchable Solemn, made better by our normal summon being a Zombie. 3 Red, 1 White. I'm back on the white. You just need to see these, either to send them to the GY, or to search them for more value on the follow-up, so even though White is a lot worse, it really is still quite good, and even better in a deck with the Zombies engine. I think you need to play 3 Eldland 3 Golden Lord. Here's my reasoning: Seeing Eldland is always better than seeing Lord. But if 2 Lords get banished you want your cards to still work that third turn. So even though 5 might be a better ratio for "Golden Lords" I think 6 is still the right number, you want to see your lord, you want to see your Eldland, you don't mind seeing them together. That left room in the deck for a small Zombies package. 1 Shiranui Solitaire and 3 Uni-Zombie seemed like the right number of Uni-Zombie to run. You actually don't want to brick on this card as much as you do at 5 copies in this version of the deck, but you do want the consistency boost up to the 4th copy. I only wanted to run the 1 Bloom and the one Balerdroch. These cards all play pretty nicely with the Eldlich Engine, and are mostly here to support that, but also put up Zombie World even more consistently in matchups where Zombie World is good while being useful Eldlich utility cards in their own right. This small Zombies package best mitigates the "schizophrenia" problem the deck could have with a more Zombie World focused plan. That left room for 1 card, and I wanted it to be a consistency booster, and if it was a 1 of I wanted it to be more impactful than Upstart. Performapal Popperup carries a potentially high cost in life points, in exchange for letting you discard 3 to draw 3. Holy crap. Even better, since you discard UP TO 3. Yet nobody plays this card. And the reason is pretty simple, it is just Ash bait, and if you get Ashed you've just discarded a card, or potentially a bunch of cards, for no value. But tbh it being Ash bait is pretty good IMO, especially since it sets up my Gy even if it does get Ashed, and if it doesn't it'll turn mediocre hands into explosive ones single handedly. The card is particularly powerful in Eldlich since you want your cards in the GY so much and can set your cards to minimize lifepoint loss. I don't love it as card advantage enough to run 3 of it, I don't even necessarily want to see it that often, but sending for cost alone makes this card pretty worthwhile IMO.  In tuning I've decided to try a second copy of the countertrap. It's just really good in this deck and easily searchable, and you often want to search a second after using the first.  Ice Dragon's Prison is really good in Zombie World decks, by virtue of Zombie World making all monsters on the field and in the GY Zombies, so I switched to that plan. I also decided you really do only need 2 of Cursed Eldland. The card is nuts, but with the consistency boost provided by Zombie cards, you have enough access to Golden Lord that you want to brick out less on the Eldland. That left room to move an Ice Dragon's Prison to the main, the card is a huge blow-out with Zombie World, and we'll usually make Zombie World, and on top of that the card usually won't be dead. This frees up 1 slot in the side, for Red Reboot against other Trap.decks.  In further tuning I'm back on the hand traps in the side, and I remembered Called and Zeus are cards so I threw them in.

deck_excerpt: Testing Deck, currently on a goal to make Fallen of Albaz playable. That being said, I think my deck is pretty good, though it could use more interrup
deck_description: Honestly, I'm trying to make Fallen of Albaz playable. So far, I think this deck is pretty good, though it can be way better. It does brick if you don't draw the right combo. That being said, I have played through bricks and somehow I have won those matches. Then again, my opponent was bricking at times. I'll post the combos later, but don't hesitate to offer advice or some critique.  Alright, if you go first, you better hope you get "Aluber, Jester of Despia" and another "Despia" monster (either "Tragedy" or "Dramaturge" (preferably the latter)). Along with a "Nadir Servant" ( though you can still make plays without it).  Normal Summon the "Aluber", search for the "Theather", or if you already have it in your hand then search for "Branded Opening".  Use your "Theater" to fusion "Aluber" and "Dramaturge" and summon "Masquerade the Blazing Dragon" then Special Summon "Dramaturge" from the grave in Atk position. The "Masquerade" will constantly charge your opponent 600LP for every card and effect activated. And you can choose when to use "Dramaturge" effect to negate a monster's effect whenever an Extra Deck Monster is Special Summoned. So choose carefully. Not only that, your "Aluber" is in the GY, just waiting in the graveyard for your opponent to remove your fusion monster on the field.  Well, the Dogmatika package is pretty simple, send an extra deck monster ("Albion the Branded Dragon" or "Titaniklad the Ash Dragon") add your "Dogmatika Ecclesia" then you special and add the "Fleurdelis" (or the "Dogmatika Punishment") and end your turn. During the end phase, "Albion" will activate and you go ahead and set a Judgement of the Branded from deck to your back row (or if you sent "Titaniklad the Ash Dragon", just add the Fleurdelis). It honestly comes in handy. Just a reminder, that "Dogmatika Punishment" is a double-edged sword, especially in a Fusion-based deck like this. So try to use "Dogmatika Punishment" as a last resort only.

Official Card Game (遊☆戯☆王オフィシャルカードゲーム, Yū-Gi-Ō Ofisharu Kādo Gēmu) in Asia, is a Japanese collectible card game developed and published by Konami. It is based on the fictional game of Duel Monsters created by manga artist Kazuki Takahashi, which is the main plot device during the majority of the manga franchise, Yu-Gi-Oh, and its various anime adaptations and spinoff series.  "D/D/D" (ＤディーＤディーＤディー Dīdīdī), known as DDD in the English manga, and pronounced "Triple D" in the dubbed anime, is a sub-archetype of the "D/D" archetype used by Declan Akaba in the Yu-Gi-Oh! ARC-V anime and special manga chapter. The "D/D/D" monsters serve as the "bosses" of the "D/D" archetype due to most of the archetype's gameplay focusing on their Summoning, along with the fact that "D/D/D" monsters generally have higher ATK/DEF and stronger effects than non-"D/D/D" "D/D" monsters. deck_excerpt: A fun and competitive way to play Charmer Deck by using the right cards and strategies, which they're no longer unplayable as before in 2021 with the
deck_description: How to Play Charmer Start with only using 3 simple Key Cards which is the only best I ever come out with for the Full Charmer's combos. Just following the recommendation cards that are listed below. ___________________________________________ [Key Cards]: 3 Main Engine - Spirit Charmers - Performage Damage Juggler - Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame [Recommend] to Search/Use - Lyna the Light Charmer (Hand) & Awakening of the Possessed (Spell/Trap Zone) - Performage Trick Clown (Hand) - Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden (Spell/Trap Zone) = Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires (Hand) ___________________________________________ Once you finally set up your cards. You will proceed with the next step by activating “Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires” effect to send out “Lyna, the Light Charmer” from your hand to the GY. Then use "Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires" effect to become Earth Attribute that allowed you to Summon “Awakening of the Possessed - Nefariouser Archfiend'' card from either hand or Deck by sending both “Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires” and “Performage Trick Clown” from the field to the GY, which make them to trigger of their effects by Chain Link 2 and bringing it back “Lyna, the Light Charmer” from the GY to the field along with “Performage Trick Clown” by it own effect. Now you have finally had a chance to Summon “Familiar-Possessed Lyna” from either hand or Deck by its own effect. After that use “Familiar-Possessed Lyna” effect to search out “Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous” from your Deck then add it to your hand which is the only best Spellcaster monster with 1500 DEF/Level 4/Light Attribute monster that can be able to search out by "Familiar-Possessed - Dharc" effect when it Summoned by it own effect. Reminder: Do not activate "Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous" effect during your turn when it Summoned to your field, it will disable you for summoning from the Exta Deck unless if you have too. (This is an Optional) You will soon basically understand the concept of which cards you might ever use during the set up once you finally figure out how the Charmer's strategy works. Do the rest which I already listed of all the cards that might be used for the final board set up at the below. ___________________________________________ [End Board] • Field: - Borreload Salvage Dragon - I:P Masquerena + {Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous = Selene, Queen of the Magicians} (Opponent's Turn) • Spell/Trap: - Awakening of the Possessed (face-up) - Possessed Partnerships (set) = Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous (Opponent's Turn) - Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden (Spell/Trap Zone)(Equipped by "Borreload Salvage Dragon" effect) • Hand: - 1 Draw (Your turn) - Extra Draw (During your Opponent's Turn) - Added: Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted (During your Opponent's Turn) ___________________________________________ Tips: You might not actually get them from the opening hand with exactly cards. So I prefer you to try something else with different cards in your hand if one of the Key Cards are missing. You should better rely on your additional cards in your hand that might help you to set up your cards. Keep it in your mind that "Spirit Charmers" is just an additional card to use Familiar-Possessed - Lyna's Effect to search out "Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous" from your deck to the hand. Since Lyna & Dharc familiar monsters haven’t been revealed yet in TCG. I came up with those ideas by adding “Black Dragon Collapserpent” and “White Dragon Wyverburster” from the Deck to gain more consistency. I didn't actually plan to add them on my Deck in the first place since I want to prove that this Deck can win without relying on any Limited cards.  I might actually replace the “Black Dragon Collapserpent” and “White Dragon Wyverburster” including the “Chaos Space” later once the Light and Dark familiar’s monster has been finally released in TCG. By replacing it with two copies of “Grand Spiritual Art - Ichirin” Field Spell card and one “Terraforming” Spell card. ___________________________________________ [Additional] for more Consistency You can use "Summoner Monk" as additional for "Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame" or any Level 4 monster from your Deck like "Rilliona, the Magistus of Verre" or any Performage monster depending what card you need. Requirement: 1 any Spell card, except "Spirit Charmers" card, if not, you can use it as well if you have too. deck_excerpt: Your Monsters? You mean OUR Monsters?!
deck_description: Ever wanna deck that screams... Communism? Like... Haha, Our Monsters? Presenting Lair Control!  The decks main purpose is to set backrow whilst maintaining a scary board presence that in a form of Super Poly. Lair Of Darkness States: "All monsters on the field become DARK Attribute" What better way to abuse this privilege than to throw in Super Poly into the mixture so you can make monsters with that of your opponents. And who said Communism isn't Fun? Spicy Tech cards with Super Poly-ish effects such as Fallen of Albaz and The Dark - Hex-Sealed Fusion help make this strategy even more of a control method, granting the deck 9 Super Polys in total.  Traps are Superior in this deck with the help of Lilith, Lady of Lament granting you a guarantee trap you need if you play 3 copies, such as Infinite Impermanence, The Paleozoics, Back to the Front (which is busted with Lilith), and Dogmatika Punishment.

deck_excerpt: A deck that utilizes the power of Calculator and Gren Maju with the help of the Shiranuis.
deck_description:
The goal of this deck is to summon either Gren Maju Da Eiza or Calculator and make both of them gain tremendous ATK and DEF points with the help of Shiranuis. Shiranuis are good at swarming and banishing themselves out of the play to activate their innate effects. They can also return either to the field, GY or deck with the help of their support cards. Gren Maju Strategy: Using the effects of Dimensional Fissure, Pot of Desires, Pot of Extravagance, Golden Castle of Stromberg, Pot of Prosperity, Shiranui Style Samsara, Shiranui Squiresaga and Shiranui Samurai, this will increase Gren Maju Da Eiza's ATK and DEF dramatically. (possible ATK/DEF gain: 20,000+) Tips:
  • Pot of Desires is good if you already have Gren Maju during your first 5 draws. You can just banish cards without worry. It is best paired during the first draw with anti-summon, anti-spells/traps and anti-monster effect cards like Solemns, Ash Blossom and Ice Dragon's Prison.
  • If you don't have Gren Maju during your first 5 draws, swarm the field with Shiranuis and use them as a material to link summon Shiranui Skillsaga Supremacy which has a beneficial effect for FIRE monsters in which they can't be destroyed by battle. With this, once you summon Gren Maju, it will not be destroyed by battle and you can use cards that can banish other cards freely.
Calculator Strategy: By swarming the field with high level Shiranui Synchro monsters, you can dramatically increase Calculator's ATK. (possible ATK gain: 11,400. This is the sum of all Shiranui Synchro Monsters except 1 Shiranui Samuraisaga just to have a space for calculator to be summoned.) Tips:
  • Prevent Calculator's destruction by using your anti-magic/trap/summon/monster effect cards.

deck_excerpt: Evil Eyes for the October 2021 format
deck_description: Evil Eyes are actually lowkey kind of a good strategy when you cut out the filler. At the very least it has potential, I actually like the synergies between it an Eldlich. But ultimately I think a purer version of the deck can still compete. Don't get me wrong, there are reasons the deck is underexplored, and it probably won't be a tier 1 strategy any time soon, but the core of the deck is really good. You Normal Summon Serziel, then turn his ability on with Evil Eye of Selene, giving you one pop on an opponent's turn and a boss monster with great protection. This 1 card 1 interruption schtick has proven to be good enough in the past, and having other useful spells and traps to search if you see the Evil Eye of Selene is pretty boss too. In addition, it has a Field Spell that searches it.  So, when building an Evil Eye deck you have to consider which element to build around, are you a more "combo"ish Zerziel Turbo or are you Serziel Stun. The elements for both of these are okay. I ultimately decided on playing a very small Evil Eye package featuring none of the extra-deck monsters. I think this plays to Serziel's strengths better than playing the more comboish version, and I discovered this when melding the engine with Eldlich. You don't actually need to play a lot of Evil Eye cards outside of the core engine, the combos you are giving up aren't good enough, whereas Serziel by itself if at the very least close. My thought was to make this a dumb trap deck - summon Serziel, set 4 backrow is the nuts in this deck.  So, I started with tech cards. I'm not sure I'll stick to this system, but for now deciding on Tech Cards first is something I'm adopting into my deckbuilding process. This allows me to figure out what interactions I am playing ahead of my engine, so that I'm less inclined to "cut" tech cards in my deckbuilding process. Solemn Judgement IMO is obligatory in this type of deck - if you're playing a trap deck Lightning Storm and Evenly Matched and even Twin Twisters will ruin your day if you don't run this card. It could easily be in the side for games 2 and 3 but I like the card and it is a staple in my decks, because it is so versatile and powerful. Solemn Strike was added in the same breath, it's just a strong versatile card that is great going first and still very good going second, and a staple in successful Trap decks. Next I wanted a little spice. 2 Dogmatika Punishment made a lot of sense to me, but I wanted to run Trap Trick for essentially extra copies of this. With Trap Trick you're effectively running 4 Dogmatika Punishment for some purposes, but won't mind seeing the two of them together. For hand Traps I'm running 3 Imperm and 3 Dimension Shifter. Imperm is high enough impact, and doubles as a useful spell for Trap Trick to set, that it is worth running. D Shifter is potentially huge, we don't really play the GY game in this version of the deck and D Shifter is such a high impact hand trap that it is absolutely worth maining in basically any deck that can run it. Then I'm running 2 Evil Eye Retribution. You need at least 1 copy of this for when you see Evil Eye of Selene, but I think 2 gives us 5 cards Lightning Storm which is huge IMO. It also can't be negated if you have Evil Eye of Selene equipped to Serziel, though the downside is it does nothing if you don't see a Serziel. Evil Eye Defeat is also a huge interaction card, basically a 2 for 1 if you're strategy is online. We would only run 1 of these for the purposes of searching, but we need 2 to be able to use this off of Trap Trick. This way Trap Trick should almost always have something to set (and usually activate on resolution).  The next step was to throw in my Pot cards. As I said, you really need to see Serziel for the deck to do its thing, and the fact that it can play Prosperity and Duality for free is actually a huge upside for the deck. The pots don't even conflict, it is so insane.  After that it is 3 of the Field Spell with Terraforming, 3 Serziel, and 1 Evil Eye of Selene, your brick or Taketemborg for the engine. Evil Eye of Selene can reset itself, , so I think 1 copy of it is fine. It does leave you a little more vulnerable to Twin Twisters, but not by much. The Field Spell is always better to see than Serziel himself, since when Serziel pops you own card you can give up the Field Spell instead of something valuable. Regardless, I think you need all 7 copies of Serziel to play the Evil Eye engine. Sadly, you really don't need much else.  That left 6 spots in the deck, which was just perfect. I wanted to run packages of Floodgates that combo together, and to avoid bricking I thought packages of 2 made a lot of sense. So from just having put in everything I wanted I had the exact room to put in 2 Rivalry, the weakest floodgate but meta relevant and combos with There Can Be Only One, There Can Be Only One, the strongest individual floodgate that again combos with Rivalry of Warlords, and Summon Limit, which doesn't directly combo with either but puts a second limitation on opponents that combined with the first will frustrate them. These also have the advantage of being continuous spells, meaning you can pop them with Evil Eye cards after they've already done their job.  Punishment really didn't jive with the D Shifter in the deck, so it got cut for an Artifact Package. What is nice is that popping these cards yourself with Serziel lets you pop another card, so even if Scythe is dead Sanctum still puts in work in this deck. Scythe is also just really good, and is even half-decent to set a lot of the time.  In tuning I settled on a second copy of Selene because while it can be bricky, seeing it is nice, and it gives the deck a backup plan if your first is banished. I actually basically did what I always do and rebuilt the deck from the bottom up again, this time incorporating a couple copies of Zombie World. This card is decent as a floodgate in it's own right right now, but is notable for combing with Rivalry and There Can Be Only One very effectively. The idea is to have floodgates that are good on their own, but also combo with each other, and Zombie World fits that bill right now. The other notable new inclusion is 2 copies of crackdown. Much as I love the artifact engine in Evil Eye, when you only have 2 spaces to fill Crackdown is notable for stealing an opponent's monster to pop once it's on your side of the field, and means we might actually use our extra deck when our floodgates will let us. I still think 5 spell/trap negates is plenty, since when you see 1 of your copies of Selene you can search Retribution.

Hello there, this is my new attempt on the Majespecter archetype. It is more of a "pure" version of the deck and I think this way, it is much stronger! Strategy The Strat is simple, set scales, pendulum summon as much as you can, search for traps and stop your opponent from playing Yu-Gi-OH! !! Turn three, you try to otk with Number S39: Utopia the Lightning. (that is also your plan going second) Card highlights Antihuman Intelligence ME-PSY-YA - ME-PSY-YA is a very powerful new pendulum card. It is a generic low scale with no restrictions, but an interesting floodgate effect. It banishes all spell and trap cards that would go to the GY while placed in the pendulum zone. This effect helps against decks that rely on floating or recycling spell and trap cards like Sky Striker and Eldlich. ME-PSY-YA' monster effect is quite strong as well, but not too important for this deck. Its main purpose is to be a low scale for the deck. Saambell the Star Bonder - While Saambell is not as strong as I initially believed, it is shares the same type and attribute as the Majespectors. It is a target for Ties of the Brethren and helps to go into Totem Bird, thanks to it being level three. Servant of Endymion - Servant's only purpose is to be a low scale for the deck while also being a target for Ties of the Brethren. Together with Spell Power Mastery, I play three copies of it. Secret Village of the Spellcasters - Village is a difficult one. I have seen many deck lists maining Village. The problem I see is that the Majespecters are getting tributed from the field to activate their traps and spells, eventually leaving you with no spellcasters on the field, resulting in Village to lock you down and not your opponent. Maybe I am too paranoid in that regard. It is still a strong floodgate against certain decks, so I decided to play it in the side deck.   The side deck presents some accountable options, but can be customized at will. Suggestions to improve the deck are welcome. :) Have a nice day, everyone!

Cosmic Dragons Strategy

The best opening hand consists of Doppelwarrior, Junk Converter, and any Tuner monster. First, activate Junk Converter's effect to discard itself and a tuner in your hand and add Junk Synchron to your hand (if you already have Junk Synchron, you can add Jet Synchron to your hand ) Normal Summon Junk Synchron, then use its effect to Special Summon Junk Converter from GY, and Special Summon Doppelwarrior from your hand. Synchro Summon Junk Speeder to EMZ using Junk Synchron and Junk Converter. Cl 1 Junk Speeder cl 2 Junk Converter. Special Summon Junk Synchron from GY and Road Synchron, Fleur Synchron, Jet Synchron. Synchro Summon Red Supernova Dragon to EMZ using Junk Speeder, Junk Synchron, Road Synchron, Fleur Synchron (If you have Jet Synchron in your hand, Special Summon it using Fleur Synchron's effect). Synchro Summon Martial Metal Marcher using Jet Synchron and Doppelwarrior. Cl 1 Martial Metal Marcher cl 2 Doppelwarrior. Special Summon 2 Tokens and Junk Syncchron from GY. Activate Jet Synchron's effect to bring it back from GY (if you already have a Jet Synchron on the field, then Cl1 Martial Metal Marcher Cl2 Jet Synchron to search Junk Synchron from Deck Cl3 Doppelwarrior). Synchro Summon Celestial Double Star Shaman using Jet Synchron and a Token. Use Celestial Double Star Shaman's effect to Special Summon Doppelwarrior from GY. Synchro Summon T.G. Hyper Librarian using Celestial Double Star Shaman, Doppelwarrior, a Token. Use Doppelwarrior's effect, Summon 2 Tokens. Synchro Summon Herald of the Arc Light using Junk Synchron and a Token. Synchro Summon Cosmic Blazar Dragon using Martial Metal Marcher, Herald of the Arc Light, T.G. Hyper Librarian. So your end board consist of a monster that can nuke your opponent board, a omni negate and a Lv1 token to Synchro Summon in your next turn. There is another way to end in the exactly same board. If you manage to have Junk Synchron, Doppelwarrior on your field and Jet Synchron in your hand, you can Synchro Summon Junk Speeder using Junk Synchron and Doppelwarrior. Cl1 Junk Speeder Cl2 Doppelwarrior, Summon 2 Tokens and Junk Synchron, Road Synchron, Fleur Synchron from your Deck. Synchro Summon Red Supernova Dragon to EMZ using Junk Speeder, Junk Synchron, Road Synchron, Fleur Synchron. Special Summon Jet Synchron from your hand using Fleur Synchron's effect. Synchro Summon Celestial Double Star Shaman using a token and Jet Synchron. Cl1 Celestial Double Star Shaman Cl2 Jet Synchron. Add Junk Converter to your hand, Special Summon Doppelwarrior from GY and Junk Converter from your hand. Synchro Summon T.G. Hyper Librarian using Celestial Double Star Shaman, Junk Converter and a token. Special Summon Jet Synchron from GY using Junk Converter. Synchro Summon Martial Metal Marcher using Jet Synchron and Doppelwarrior. Cl1 T.G. Hyper Librarian Cl2 Martial Metal Marcher Cl3 Doppelwarrior. Summon 2 tokens, Special Summon Junk Synchron from GY. Synchro Summon Herald of the Arc Light using Junk Synchron and a token. Synchro Summon Cosmic Blazar Dragon using Martial Metal Marcher, Herald of the Arc Light, T.G. Hyper Librarian.

deck_excerpt: Ideia diferente e massa pra jogar de Megálito (Megalith)
deck_description:
E aí, pessoal. Tudo certo? Espero que sim.

Hoje eu venho abordar minhas experimentações com Megalindos (English: "Megalith"/ Português BR: "Megálitos"), "Diabretiço" ( English: "Impcantation") e as "Artes de Ritual Superior e Avançada" (English: "High/Advanced Ritual Art"). Antes vou introduzir um pouquinho sobre a jogabilidade base dos "Megálitos". Se você não estiver interessado ou se já souber tudo sobre o arquétipo, fique à vontade para pular essa parte.

Introdução

"Megálito" é um arquétipo de Monstros Rituais do tipo Rocha com atributo TERRA e que se destacam por não terem uma magia ritual própria. Ao invés disso, os próprios monstros do arquétipo substituem as Magias Rituais, o que é ótimo por reduzirem 1 ⁄ 3 os requisitos para uma Invocação Ritual.

Todos os membros do arquétipo tem o efeito de se invocar por Invocação Ritual entre si, além de um efeito particular de cada monstro. Eles podem ser separados em 3 grupos de acordo com seu LV e função na estratégia.

Grupo 1: Monstros de LV 8 (parte agressiva/defensiva)

Esse grupo tem a função de invocar os Monstros Rituais "Megálito" da mão, ao se enviarem como custo e tributando monstros cuja soma dos LVs seja igual ou maior do que o LV do monstro a ser invocado. Tenha em mente que, infelizmente, o monstro enviado para o GY e que está invocando outro por Invocação Ritual não têm seu LV contado para a soma, apesar de enviá-los ainda ser o custo do efeito de invocar. Além do efeito de Invocação Ritual, cada um deles têm efeitos diferentes quando em campo. Ambos os efeitos de cada monstro são Hard Once Per Turn. São eles:

"Aratron": este serve como uma hand trap durante a Fase Principal, pois seu efeito de invocar 1 monstro "Megálito" da mão é um Efeito Rápido. Isso é ótimo porque: 1. Você pode pegar seu oponente de surpresa, destruindo o campo do seu oponente com "Bethor" no turno 1 do oponente; 2. Te permite esquivar de efeitos que dão alvo nos seus monstros, fazendo os efeitos deles passarem mesmo tomando "Impermanência Infinita" ("Infinite Impermanence''), por exemplo. Seu outro efeito, em campo, é: "Quando seu oponente ativar um card ou efeito que dê alvo em um card que você controla (Efeito Rápido): você pode colocar um Monstro Ritual do seu GY no fundo do Deck; negue a ativação, e se isso acontecer, destrua-o." Eu acho muito feio quem roda menos que 3 em qualquer decklist;

"Bethor": "Se for invocado por Invocação Ritual: você pode dar alvo em cards que seu oponente controla até o número de Monstros Rituais com nomes diferentes no GY; destrua-os". Ótima carta, mas, apesar do potencial, você precisa preparar seu campo e GY para fazer bom uso dele. Eu gosto de rodar 2, mas não julgo quem roda menos que isso;

"Phaleg": é o powerhouse do Deck. Enquanto ele estiver em campo, todos os seus monstros ganham 300 ATK/DEF para cada Monstro Ritual no GY. Não é raro você ficar com 3 ou 4 monstros com mais de 2500 de ATK quando ele entra em jogo. Mesma coisa que "Bethor", eu gosto de rodar 2, mas também não julgo quem roda menos que isso.

Grupo 2: Monstros de LV 4 (buscadores/extendedores)

Todos eles têm um efeito de invocar 1 Monstro Ritual da mão ao tributar monstros, incluindo eles mesmos, cuja soma dos LVs seja igual ou maior do que o LV do monstro a ser invocado. Esse efeito é hard once per turn. E cada um deles têm um efeito ao serem invocados por Invocação Ritual, e esses não são hard once per turn.

"Ophiel": "Se este card for invocado por Invocação Ritual: você pode adicionar 1 monstro "Megálito" do seu Deck à mão". Buscador que busca quantas vezes você puder invocar ele no mesmo turno. Preciso falar que é 3 no Deck? Preciso, né? Roda 3.

"Hagith": "Se este card for invocado por Invocação Ritual: você pode adicionar 1 card de Magia/Armadilha "Megálito" do Deck à mão". Buscador de backrow. Esse Deck ama backrow, mas não o suficiente para 3 Hagith. Eu gosto de usar só 1 porque o que não falta é jeito de buscar ou reciclar ele nesse deck.

"Och": "Se este card for invocado por Invocação Ritual: você pode comprar 1 card e descartar 1 card". Mas esse não é o talento dele. Ele se diferencia dos outros LV 4 porque pode invocar da mão qualquer Monstro Ritual em Velocidade de Magia 2. É por causa desse carinha que a galera gosta tanto de rodar "Shinobarão Pavão" ("Shinobaron Peacock"). Roda de preferência 1 pelo mesmo motivo que o "Hagith".

Grupo 3: "Phul", o Foda

"Megálito Phul" é um Monstro Ritual de nível 2 que "Se este card for invocado por Invocação Ritual: você pode dar alvo em 1 Monstro Ritual no seu GY; o seu LV se torna igual ao alvo e depois adicione o alvo à mão". Além disso, "Durante a Fase Principal (Efeito Rápido): você pode ativar este efeito; Invoque 1 Monstro Ritual "Megálito" da sua mão ou deck tributando monstros da mão e/ou campo cuja soma dos LVs seja igual ou maior que o LV do monstro invocado". Ele busca, recicla e pode interromper o turno do oponente. Só seria melhor se desse um impeachment no Salnorabo. Se puder, roda 5.

O Problema do Deck

O problema é que os Monstros Rituais do arquétipo necessários para começar a invocar outros monstros são de nível 8, ou seja, não podem ser buscados com "Preparação de Rituais" (English: "Preparation of Rites"), muito menos por "Pré-Preparação de Rituais" (English: "Pre-Preparation of Rites"), o que reduz muito a consistência necessária para fazer o que o Deck deveria fazer. O arquétipo conta com alternativas de busca, por meio dos monstros de LV 4 e LV 2, mas que, para buscarem, precisam ser invocados por Invocação Ritual (｡ŏ﹏ŏ). O Deck também conta com uma Magia Rápida que invoca por Invocação Ritual 1 "Megálito" direto do deck, que, por ser uma Magia Rápida, também não pode usufruir de suportes genéricos de Rituais, dependendo, assim, dos meios do próprio Deck.

 Aí entram os "Diabretiços", que não só aumentam a consistência do Deck, buscando as cartas Rituais chaves do Deck, mas também gera monstros para tributar para Invocações Ritual, sem falar nos combos com "Soberano da Vaidade" ("Vanity's Ruler") e o "Zaborg o Mega Monarca" ("Zaborg the Mega Monarch"). Só que "Megálito", por não ter Magias de Rituais próprias, deixa embaçado para usar o "Velaneco" ("Impcantation Candoll") e o "Livropedra" ("Impcantation Brookstone"), restando praticamente metade da engine.

Fora tudo isso, eu me canso fácil quando diferentes Decks, por terem a mesma engine ("Nekroz", "Shinobird", etc.), acabam ficando repetitivos e, por fim, enjoativo para a minha gameplay. Por isso eu tento misturar com outras engines para variar, por exemplo, trocar os "Diabretiços" por "Dogmatikas" ao jogar de "Nekroz".

Daí eu comecei a gastar massa cinzenta para deixar o "Megálito'' mais diferente de outros Decks que rodam a mesma engine.

Então, depois de gastar muito ATP e horas de experimentação, acabei com a seguinte lista. Vamos abordar o que têm de diferença de outras builds comuns de "Megálitos''.

"Dragão Branco de Olhos Azuis" ("Blue-Eyes White Dragon") e "Dragão de Alexandrita" ("Alexandrite Dragon"): alvo para as "Artes de Ritual'' para trazer os monstros dos dois grupos. A escolha desses dois monstros se dá principalmente pelo LV 4 e 8, e também por terem a capacidade máxima de ATK dentre os vanillas.

"Arte de Ritual Avançada": ajuda bastante a pôr os primeiros monstros em campo sem gastar muito esforço, por enviarem os tributos do Deck. Te ajuda, também, a economizar os Rituais de LV 8 para que você possa usá-los de forma mais agressiva. E, por último mas não menos importante, você tem mais alvos para "Velaneco" e "Livropedra", deixando eles mais viáveis e o Deck mais consistente. Esse último argumento também serve para a "Arte de Ritual Superior".

"Arte de Ritual Superior": Traz Monstros do Deck. Ótimo para trazer os LVs 4 pro campo e realizar as buscas e ótimo também para deixar os LVs 8 também mais acessíveis.

Conclusão

Acredito que tenha resolvido os problemas do Deck que apontei anteriormente por meio dessas ações. Não tenho nada contra as engines genéricas, tanto que até continuei as utilizando. Só acho que quando roda o "Soberano da Vaidade"/"Mega Zaborg" fica meio repetitivo e reduz a versatilidade do Deck, deixando a condição de vitória dependente de poucas cartas que não são tão acessíveis o tempo todo.

Apesar disso tudo, não acho que ele tenha ficado OP Tier 0 1 card combo, mas acredito que desse jeito seja a forma mais divertida e consistente que você pode esperar desse Deck até então.

Valeuzão! Espero ter ajudado! E até a próxima ideia… ...se pá

deck_excerpt: Vroom Vroom that is kinda easy on the wallet
deck_description: In my quest to get a budget deck of every summoning method, after seeing Gage playing it on progression series i decided that would be the pick for Synchros and here we are  The deck manages to do some cool stuff if you open decently and the search power is amazing if you can blow up the field spells, Pit stop acts like a little pot of greed and if you banish it special summons and Test Run increases the level of your monsters and destroys one card on the field.  As for some plays going into Dawn Dragster manages to negate spells and traps, Shining Star gets counters to negate and destroy monsters and Dark Dragster is not a hard once per turn spot removal.  Scrap Dragon blows up your field spells so you get a search and blow up a card on the field, but if you are feeling destructive and want a board wipe it's very easy to access Black Rose Dragon  It manages to do some cool stuff and it's less than 10 euros, so i hope you guys enjoy it!

deck_name: Red-Eyes Black Dragon + Mirror Force Dragon
deck_excerpt: This is a combination of Red-Eyes Black Dragon AND Mirror Force Dragon, because I thought the two go together. Remove it if you like, it won't hurt an
deck_description: This deck contains the usual Red-Eyes cards as well as the materials needed to summon Mirror Force Dragon- possibly the worst things to put in one of these decks.     Using Insight, you can send one Red-Eyes and add one Spirit to your hand. You set spirit and chain it when you can- except to a Raigeki or other cards that remove your monsters.  You can use Cards of the Red Stone to get a pot of greed AND allow for one more use of the aforementioned Insight.  You can also use the XYZ monster to really quickly fill up the board- one Red-Eyes per turn. The turn you activate it- 2800 [from the XYZ monster] plus 2400 [from the Red-Eyes you summon by detaching material] = 5200 attack total. The next turn you add 2400 [from another detach] making it 7600 ATK. Over the 2 turns you deal over 12,000 ATK, and is enough to kill the player from full LP. All you need is 2 Red-Eyes monsters.     You can easily get Red-Eyes Alternative by discarding one Red-Eyes, or even the Alternative.  There are many more combos but these are the ones that come to mind.

deck_excerpt: Pure Exorsisters Deck. Summon your XYZ monsters to punish your opponent for using their graveyard!
deck_description: This is my current work-in-progress pure Exorsister deck.  My build here is a lot more slower-paced compared to some other Exorsister lists. Instead of turboing out Mikhaelise to search Vadis, I opted to run more traps and sit on main deck monsters.     The Game Plan:  Summon the main deck Exorsisters to try to proc them on your opponent's turn and utilize traps to interrupt your opponent's plays.     My thoughts on plays:  I normally don't really like summoning Mikhaelise turn 1, opting instead to just keep the main deck monsters on the field, but Mikahelise turn 1 is definitely not a bad idea. Depending on the matchup and your opening hand, Mikhaelise turn 1 can help shape your board around the opponent and round out your plays. However, the deck is not all Exorsister. This deck runs some traps to help back up your sisters. This deck runs Traptrick to help turbo out sisters using Vadis, but it could also search out other traps in case you open Vadis or search it with Mikhaelise. IDP is great against some decks and if used properly can end turns. Imperm is nice because it can be a hand trap and a normal trap. Speaking of hand traps, this deck also runs Dimension Shifter. Dimension Shifter on its own can also end turns. If you open Dimension Shifter turn 1, you can just normal summon a main deck sister to keep Dimension Shifter active.     Some of my card choices explained:  Some things I think this deck struggles with are hand advantage and finishing games.  When you're playing this deck, you often have to vomit out your hand. It feels almost like BA to me, except without the Cir-Dante loop. To combat this, I decided to add desires.  As for finishing games, it's a bit hard to link climb, and Vadis locks you into sisters, so I chose to run utopia the double, which does have some conflict with desires. Until I think of a better finisher, this is what I'll stick to.  I've also been thinking of messing with all of the sister ratios some more. I was originally running 3 of all the main deck sisters, but I felt like Elaine just wasn't doing much, so I decided to cut it to 2 for another copy of a trap. The ratios I have feel pretty good because you want to see at least one every turn. But I might experiment with it some more especially if I implement other engines.     My Thoughts  Overall, I've been having a lot of fun with Exorsisters. They're not the most competitive deck, but they are a lot of fun to play. Specifically, I love Carpedibel, their in-archetype prohibition. It just feels super rewarding to use. I'm thinking of experimenting with some other engines as well. I've seen some Magistus, Brave Token, and other builds that seem fun.     Please let me know if you have any thoughts or changes! Also, The side deck doesn't have much thought put into it, it's just some random stuff I threw in there.

deck_description: This is a Relinquished deck for the short-lived May 2003 format. With the introduction of Sinister Serpent in this format, Relinquished became much more powerful! deck_excerpt: A powerful magical musketeer deck mixed with amazement and dogmatika engine. Better go first to play control with lots of interruptions. On the other
deck_description:
As usual magical musketeer deck, normal summon magical musketeer monster and try to annoy your opponent with your interruptions.

Infinite Impermanence can do trigger effect of Alerkino to special summon himself from hand and even if already have an Amaze Attraction Horror House, there can be a flip face-down and a monster effect negation.

Flexible in choosing magical musket cards to beat your opponent's cards. If go first with Nadir Servant, send Wind Pegasus @Ignister, add Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous so you have 1 interruption and also 1 powerful card to play in the next turn. Better caught with instant fusion when go second and special summon 1 of the "eyes restrict" depending on situations. Can use any link 2 monsters else in alternative to Lyna the Light Charmer, Lustrous. Cuz Magical Musketeer Max can special summon many monster in the same time, the 2 boss monster,Accesscode Talker is really a powerful monster to beat your opponent and Underworld Goddess of the Closed World can be used to beat your opponent boss monster, or archetypes using graveyard and even don't let your opponent play with I:P Masquerena using its effect to special summon this boss in your opponent turn. "Exchange" can be a cool card to use as you will know what deck your opponent uses and even take their handtraps to go against him/her and also trigger magical musketeer monster effect. As the reprint of dogmatika in the mega tin 2021, the dogmatika engine is more accessible. The Borrelsword Dragon be a cheaper card to use instead of Accesscode Talker . Finally, with many back-ups and flexibilties in situations, this mixed deck is pretty cool and can even beat meta decks if using interruptions effectively. Willing to improve this deck so feel free to make comments.

deck_excerpt: Don't underestimate the power of the Nimble archetype!
deck_description:
This is good for Xyz and Link summoning high beatstick monsters using Nimble-archetype monsters.
  • Summon Nimble Beaver then special summon Nimble Musasabi to Xyz or Link summon depending on the situation.
    • If your opponent has a face-up or set spell/trap card, Link summon Knightmare Phoenix to destroy a set/face-up spell/trap card.
    • If your opponent controls a high beatstick monster that cannot be destroyed by battle, Xyz summon Sky Cavalry Centaurea, attack your opponent monster, then after the damage step, detach 1 xyz material from Centaurea to bounce your opponent's monster to their hand.
    • If your opponent controls a high beatstick monster, Xyz summon Number 64: Ronin Raccoon Sandayu, detach 1 material to special summon 1 Kagemusha Raccoon Token (its ATK becomes equal to the highest ATK monster on the field.), then the token attacks the opponent monster.
    • Optional summons: Missus Radiant, Mistar Boy, Masquerena and Relinquished Anima.
  • If Nimble Sunfish is destroyed by battle, send Nimble Angler to the graveyard to trigger its effect (Nimble Angler's effect: When this monster is send from hand or deck to the GY, special summon 2 Nimble monsters from your deck to the field except Nimble Angler), then trigger Sunfish's effect special summon 1 Nimble Sunfish to field from your deck. Now, there are 3 monsters on the field. You can:
    • Xyz summon Paleozoic Anomalocaris (3 materials or more) for high beatstick and immunity from card effects.
    • Xyz summon Number 29: Mannequin Cat (2 materials only), activate its effect to detach 1 monster, target 1 monster on your opponent's GY and special summon it to his/her field then target 1 monster from your opponent's field and special summon 1 monster of the same type or attribute as the target monster. Now you have a total of 3 monsters again on your field (1 Mannequin, 1 monster and 1 new special summoned monster). You can use these monsters to Link summon (it's up to you if you want to link summon or not.)
  • If Nimble Musasabi was destroyed by your opponent and he/she has 3 or more monsters and have either 1 or 2 monster zones available, special summon 2 Musasabi on his/her side of the field then activate Nibiru, the Primal Being quick effect to tribute all your opponent's monster to special summon 1 Primal Being Token to your opponent's field and stop them from their combo summons.
  • Super-Nimble Mega Hamster has the same method as Nimble Beaver but it takes longer to do some Xyz or Link summoning.
  • Obedience Schooled is good during your first turn or when you don't have any monster on your side of the field because you can summon 3 level 2 beast monsters with different names which is a good setup for Xyz summoning Mannequin Cat, Centaurea, and Sandayu which are beast-type monsters.
  • Bubble Bringer stops level 4 or higher monster from attacking and also, you send this card to the GY to special summon 2 level 3 or lower WATER monsters from the GY to the field to use as a Xyz or Link summon material.

deck_excerpt: Updated february 2022, Despia Darklord deck very consistent and fun to play Decklist tried 200+ times
deck_description:
EDIT: I have done some changing so some of the card that I wrote could not be in the deck anymore The starters are Aluber, Jester of Despia and Indulged Darklord. With Aluber, if you don't already have the field spell (Despia, Theater of the Branded), you search for that, otherwise search for Branded Opening that let you search Dramaturge of Despia or, if you have high level fusion monster in the GY, Ad Libitum of Despia. Now, with the field spell, you can fusion summon using Aluber on the field and what you have in the hand. With Indulged Darklord you want to give to the opponent Darklord Ukoback, if you can't usually the best one to give is Darklord Superbia and you want to search for Darklord Mornigstar, if you  can fusion summon into The first Darklord to nuke the board or Darklord Ixchel to cycle the deck. Some nice interactions are:
  • you can use the darklord you give to the opponent for a fusion summon using super poly
  • the second effect of The first Darklord that let you special summon a fairy monster trigger  Aluber, Indulged, Ukoback, Superbia
  • the best card to discard with Ixchel effect are the two trap cards that you can later use from the GY without paying the activation cost
  • the effects that discard cards like super poly, branded opening, allure of darkness, all of them synergize with Despian of tragedy letting you search for a despia monster
  • with golden sarcophagus if you target Despian of tragedy you trigger it's effect letting you search a despia monster and after 2 turn you take it into the hand (that's why i prefer it despite foolish burial, i found that the second effect to retrieve a speel is not that useful and i can still use it later sending Despian of tragedy to the GY with another card)
  • Darklord Superbia sometims miss timing so i reccomend to summon it at the end of a chain or outside of it
I don't like using card outside the archetype so I put staple cards in the side deck. It's very easy to summon rank 8 xyz monster and I decided to use N.38 and N.90 to cover the negating effect that the deck lacks. N.97 can be used as a finisher summoning N.100 that go easily at 9000 atk. The deck has a lot other synergies and interactions so I reccomend to try it and have fun. The deck is very very consistent and you have a dead hand 1/10 of the games, probably even less. Feel free to comment if you have any advice to improve the decklist.
ive been having lots of fun with this deck
